'''Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.''' ('''MLSE''') is a [[professional sports]] and [[commercial real estate]] company based in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].  With assets that include franchises in three of the six [[major professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada]], it is the largest sports and entertainment company in Canada, and one of the largest in North America.

The primary holdings of the company are its major sports franchises, the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]], [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] and [[Toronto FC]] of [[Major League Soccer]], as well as the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] and an [[Toronto USL Pro team|unnamed soccer team]] to be launched in the [[USL PRO]] in 2015.  In addition, it owns the [[Air Canada Centre]], the home arena of the Maple Leafs and Raptors.  MLSE also manages or has invested in several other sports facilities including [[BMO Field]], home of Toronto FC, [[Ricoh Coliseum]], home of the Marlies, [[MasterCard Centre]], the practice facility of the Maple Leafs and Marlies, [[KIA Training Ground]], practice facility for Toronto FC and home of the [[TFC Academy]], and [[Lamport Stadium]].

MLSE was founded by [[Conn Smythe]] in 1931 as Maple Leaf Gardens Limited (MLGL) to act as a [[holding company]] for the Maple Leafs and their planned new arena [[Maple Leaf Gardens]], from which the company got its name.  Smythe transferred his ownership of the Leafs to the company in exchange for shares in MLGL, and sold shares in the holding company to the public to help fund construction of the arena.  While initially primarily a hockey company, with ownership stakes in a number of [[professional ice hockey|minor]] and [[junior hockey]] clubs including the [[Toronto Marlboros]] of the [[Ontario Hockey Association]], the company later branched out to own the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] from the late 1970s to late 1980s, before merging with the Raptors, who were constructing the Air Canada Centre at the time, and adopting their current name in 1998.  Most recently the company launched Toronto FC in 2007.

Over most of its 80 plus years of existence MLSE was a [[public company]].  Following the death of majority owner [[Harold Ballard]] in 1990, [[Steve Stavro]] led a controversial bid to buy the company and take it [[Privately held company|private]].  Most recently, the  [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]] sold their 79.53% share of the company for $1.32 billion to a joint venture between [[Rogers Communications]] and [[Bell Canada]], two of Canada's largest media companies, giving the company an equity value of $1.66 billion and an enterprise value of $2 billion.  (All figures are in [[Canadian dollars]] (CAD) unless otherwise specified.)  Although the company has proven to be very profitable, they have had much less success at producing winning teams.  Of the three major franchises they currently own (Maple Leafs, Raptors and Toronto FC), only the Maple Leafs have ever won a championship, but not since their [[1967 Stanley Cup Finals|1967 Stanley Cup]].  The only other major championship the company has won was the [[74th Grey Cup]] in 1986 by the Tiger-Cats.

==Corporate history==

===Founding===
[[File:Pride at Maple Leaf Gardens.jpg|thumb|left|Maple Leaf Gardens, the former home of the Toronto Maple Leafs, after which MLGL was named]]
The corporation's roots can be traced back to 1927, when [[Conn Smythe]] organized a group of investors to purchase Toronto's premier hockey franchise, the [[Toronto St. Patricks]] of the [[National Hockey League]], which had earned [[Stanley Cup]] championships in [[1917<U+2013>18 NHL season|1918]] (as the [[Toronto Arenas]]) and [[1921<U+2013>22 NHL season|1922]], from a group headed by [[Charles Querrie]].  The club was playing poorly and minority partner [[Jack Bickell]] contacted Smythe about becoming coach of the team.  However, Smythe told Bickell that he was more interested in buying a stake in the team.  Not long after, with the team in trouble financially due to majority owner Querrie having lost a lawsuit to former [[Toronto Blueshirts]] owner [[Eddie Livingstone]], Querrie put the St. Pats up for sale and agreed in principle to sell them for $200,000 to a group that would move the team to [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=thoughages>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/12/01/maple-leafs-owners-through-the-ages/|title=Maple Leafs' owners through the ages|last=Sandler|first=Jeremy|newspaper=[[National Post]]|date=2010-12-01|accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref>  After Bickell contacted Smythe to inform him of the sale, Smythe persuaded Querrie that civic pride was more important than money and put together a syndicate that bought the St. Pats.  Smythe himself invested $10,000 of his own money and his group contributed $75,000 up front and a further $75,000 due 30 days later, with Bickell retaining his $40,000 share in the team.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=smythe>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/10/21/excerpt-the-lives-of-conn-smythe/|title=The Lives of Conn Smythe: From the Battlefield to Maple Leaf Gardens: A Hockey Icon's Story|year=2011|accessdate=2014-01-11|publisher=[[National Post]]|first=Kelly|last=McParland}}</ref>  The deal was finalized on Valentine's Day,<ref name=smythe/> and the new owners quickly renamed the team the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref name=smytheyoung>{{cite book |last1=Smythe |first1=Conn |author1link=Conn Smythe|last2=Young |first2=Scott |author2link=Scott Young (writer)|title=Conn Smythe: If you can't beat 'em in the alley |year=1981 |publisher=McClelland and Stewart |location=Toronto, Ontario |isbn=0-7710-9078-1}}</ref>{{rp|85<U+2013>86}}  Later that year, Smythe bought the [[junior hockey]] [[Toronto Marlboros]] of the [[Ontario Hockey Association]] to serve as a developmental team for Maple Leafs.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/marlies.asp|title=Marlies history|accessdate=2014-02-17|publisher=Toronto Marlies}}</ref><ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/timeline.asp|title=Marlies timeline|accessdate=2014-02-17|publisher=Toronto Marlies}}</ref>

[[File:Tor chi 94.jpg|thumb|The Toronto Maple Leafs, the primary asset of MLGL for many years, play a home game at the Gardens in 1994]]

In 1929, Smythe decided, in the midst of the [[Great Depression]], that the Maple Leafs needed a new arena. Their then home, the [[Arena Gardens]], which they shared with the Marlboros,<ref name=history/> had been built in 1912 and seated just 8,000, which the Maple Leafs were regularly filling. After considering various locations, the site at the corner of Carlton and Church was purchased from [[Eaton's|The T. Eaton Co. Ltd.]] for $350,000,<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|104}} a price said to be $150,000 below market value. A new 12,473 seat (14,550 including standing room) arena was designed by the architectural firm of [[Ross and Macdonald]]. To finance construction, Smythe got backing from [[Sun Life]] for half of the expected $1 million cost<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|103}} and launched Maple Leaf Gardens Limited (MLGL), a management company that would own both the Maple Leafs and the new arena, which was named [[Maple Leaf Gardens]] (MLG).<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|102}} A public offering of shares in MLGL was made at $10 each (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|10|1931}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars),{{inflation-fn|CA}} with a free common share for each five preferred shares purchased.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited - Prospectus|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail|The Globe]]|date=1931-03-05}}</ref> Ownership of the hockey team was transferred to MLGL in return for shares. To fund construction of the building, workers were paid 20% of their salary in MLG stock.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|104<U+2013>106}}<ref name=bigmoney>{{cite news|title=Big money always part of Gardens story|first=Paul|last=Patton|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1989-04-13}}</ref> Construction started on 1 June 1931,<ref name="startwork">{{cite news |title=New Arena Work to Start on Saturday at Midnight|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1931-05-30}}</ref> and MLG was opened five months and two weeks later, on 12 November 1931, at a cost of $1.5 million<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idCATRE5B03FL20091201|title=Toronto's Maple Leaf Gardens gets C$60 million facelift|date=2009-12-01|accessdate=2014-01-26|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens 1931 - Air Canada Centre 1999: History vs. high tech: No design marvel, Air Canada Centre struggles to graft Gardens' history into a high-tech package that bucks the retro trend|date=1999-02-13|last=Beamish|first=Mike|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref> (${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|1500000|1931}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{inflation-fn|CA}} The Marlboros also moved to the new arena.<ref name=history/>

To help fill dates at the new arena, Smythe acquired an expansion franchise in the professional [[International Lacrosse League]] on behalf of MLGL for the 1932 season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leaf Gardens granted franchise|date=1931-12-10|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref><ref name=testolympic/>  which was also given the name the [[Toronto Maple Leafs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref name=testolympic>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Local Seniors Will Test Olympic Team Tonight|date=1932-01-29|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref><ref name=twoteams/>  A team named the [[Toronto Tecumsehs (ILL)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] had competed in the first season of the ILL at the [[Arena Gardens]],<ref name=twoteams>{{cite news|title=Two Toronto teams in lacrosse loop|date=1932-01-29|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=On the highway of sports: Maroons and Leafs in lacrosse opener tonight|date=1931-06-29|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref> but was renamed the Tecumsehs with the arrival of Smythe's team.<ref name="testolympic"/><ref name=twoteams/> Both teams played at MLG.<ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leafs score decisive victory|date=1932-06-20|first=jack|last=Murray|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Tecumsehs' Victory Creates All-Round Tie|date=1932-05-09|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref> Smythe pulled out following the season due to financial losses,<ref>{{cite news|title=On The Highways of Sport: Mustangs on Rampage at U. of T.'s Expense|date=1932-10-31|last=Rodden|first=M.J.|newspaper=[[The Globe (Toronto newspaper)|Globe]]}}</ref> and the league did not play the following year.

===Minor hockey expansion===
The company has owned numerous [[minor league]] hockey teams over the years, which have served as developmental [[farm team]]s for the Maple Leafs.  A group backed by Smythe and [[Frank Selke]] of the [[Montreal Canadiens]] was awarded an [[American Hockey league]] franchise for [[Rochester, New York]] in July 1956, after a local group could not come up with the $150,000 [[United States dollars|USD]] in capital required by the league.<ref name=eager>{{cite news|last=Marcotte|first=Bob|title=Eager fans embraced arrival of the Rochester Amerks|url=http://www.democratandchronicle.com/article/20110307/NEWS0204/103070318/Eager-fans-embraced-arrival-Rochester-Amerks|newspaper=Democrat and Chronicle|date=2011-03-07|agency=Gannett Compant|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5x795iwiX|archivedate=2011-03-11|location=Rochester, New York|pages=1B,4B}}</ref><ref name=makesit>{{cite news|title=Rochester makes it - Gains AHL franchise|date=1956-07-03|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref name=coffers>{{cite news|title=Sale of Rochester hockey team pads Maple Leaf coffers|date=1966-07-07|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]|first=Neil|last=MacCarl}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Give Rochester conditional OK on AHL franchise|date=1956-06-20|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  The Leafs and Canadiens would each own 27.5% of the team, with the balance sold to Rochester interests.<ref name=eager /><ref>{{cite news|title=Maple Leafs Seek Farm Club in AHL|date=1959-03-18|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  The team was named the [[Rochester Americans]].  The Amerks were a joint affiliate of both the Canadiens and the Maple Leafs,<ref name=makesit/> though the club was operated by the Canadiens.<ref name=control>{{cite news|title=Leafs Purchase Control Of AHL Squad From Habs|date=1959-06-15|pages=22|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  In the summer of 1959 the Maple Leafs bought out the Canadiens' ownership share of the club, giving them a 55% controlling interest, due to concerns that with Montreal operating the club they were giving their prospects priority over those of the Leafs.<ref name=coffers/><ref name=control/>  They purchased most of the remaining 45% in 1963,<ref name=coffers/><ref>{{cite news|title=Rumors Have Pilous Going to Rochester|date=1963-06-05|pages=15|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=19players>{{cite news|title=19 players go: AHL franchise at Rochester sold by Leafs|date=1966-07-07|last=Rimstead|first=Paul|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> boosting their ownership share to 98% by November 1964.<ref name=exceeds>{{cite news|title=Nothing Exceeds Like Success|date=1964-11-13|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  In July 1966 the Maple Leafs sold the team to a group which included their then General Manager [[Punch Imlach]] for a reported $400,000.<ref name=coffers/><ref name=19players/><ref name=sixtyseven>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gNfXe3VrVHMC&pg=PA31|title='67: The Maple Leafs, Their Sensational Victory, and the End of an Empire|last1=Cox|first1=Damien|author1link=Damien Cox|last2=Stellick|first2=Gord|author2link=Gord Stellick|year=2009|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]]|page=31|isbn=9780470739273}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Saturday sale on shorts|date=1966-07-09|last=Beddoes|first=Dick|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Corporate reports: Maple Leaf Gardens notes drop in profit|date=1966-11-07|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|pages=25}}</ref>

In June 1963 the [[Spokane Comets]] [[Western Hockey League (1952<U+2013>74)|Western Hockey League]] franchise was purchased by a group lead by the Maple Leafs, who relocated them to become the [[Denver Invaders]] and act as the Leaf's farm team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pilous Offered Job As Boss at Denver, Leafs New Farm Club|date=1963-06-06|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs buy coast club|date=1963-06-05|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19630605&id=-LVWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=F-kDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6929,1504554|title=Spokane's Western Hockey Franchise Moves to Denver; Toronto Maple Leafs Purchase Mel Smith's Comet Stock|last=Missildine|first=Harry|date=1963-06-05|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]}}</ref><ref name=PCWHL>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=UpldzQdhpr8C&pg=PA130|title=Ice Warriors: The Pacific Coast/Western Hockey League 1948<U+2013>1974|last=Stott|first=Jon C|year=2008|publisher=Heritage House Publishing|isbn=9781927051047}}</ref> Though the league did not acknowledge that the Maple Leafs had an ownership stake in the team,<ref name=PCWHL/><ref>{{cite news|title=WHL Approves Leafs' Farm In Denver|date=1963-06-21|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> they held a majority position with the Denver partners only owning roughly 36%.<ref name=pulledout>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19640626&id=xv1VAAAAIBAJ&sjid=--IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4977,5599035|title=Invaders pulled out of Denver by Smythe|date=1964-06-26|newspaper=[[The Register-Guard]]}}</ref><ref name=retreaters/><ref name=loses>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19640626&id=ojlWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HukDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1590,3324630|title=Denver loses club|date=1964-06-26|newspaper=[[The Spokesman-Review]]}}</ref>  Following reported losses of $150,000 in their first season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs' Denver loses estimated at $150,000|date=1964-06-30|first=Milt|last=Dunnell|authorlink=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref> Smythe announced that the team would be relocated after the team failed to reach a 2,000 season ticket target by a league-imposed deadline.<ref name=PCWHL/><ref name=pulledout/><ref name=retreaters>{{cite news|title=Denver's Invaders Become Retreaters|date=1964-06-26|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=loses/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/newspage/1029529/|title=Invader Hockey club to quit Denver|date=1964-06-26|newspaper=[[Redlands Daily Facts]]}}</ref> The team became the [[Victoria Maple Leafs]] for the following season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports Briefs: Palmer Will Appear In Canadian Open|date=1964-07-18|pages=21|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  In June 1967 MLGL sold the team for $500,000 to a group from Phoenix,<ref name=sixtyseven/><ref name=PCWHL/><ref>{{cite news|title=Phoenix club charges Leafs broke contract|date=1968-05-22|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey lawsuits out of style|date=1967-09-08|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> which relocated it to become the [[Phoenix Roadrunners (WHL)|Phoenix Roadrunners]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19670517&id=I0MjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HbkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2112,4282228|title=Victoria team to Phoenix|date=1967-05-17|newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Minor pro leagues may soon merge|date=1967-06-06|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/story_print.html?id=ac72c73c-cd4f-4650-a0b6-f19c3af4fba7&sponsor=|title=At home in the desert|date=2005-11-29|accessdate=2014-02-16|newspaper=[[Times Colonist]]}}</ref>

In 1964 MLGL the [[Tulsa Oilers (1964<U+2013>84)|Tulsa Oilers]] of the [[Central Professional Hockey League]] were launched. The team was owned and operated by MLGL as a developmental club for the Maple Leafs.<ref name=exceeds/> In the spring of 1973 it was announced that the Oilers would relocate to become the [[Oklahoma City Blazers (1965<U+2013>77)|Oklahoma City Blazers]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs switch Tulsa team in CHL to Oklahoma City|date=1973-04-20|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs shift farm|date=1973-04-21|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  Prior to the 1976<U+2013>77 season the Maple Leafs decided to share an affiliate with the [[Chicago Black Hawks]] in an attempt to reduce costs,<ref>{{cite news|title=NHL clubs will cut 100 players in effort to combat rising costs|date=1976-01-31|first=Don|last=Ramsay|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|pages=43}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Some NHL rules aren't enforced at playoff time|date=1976-04-27|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> and pulled out of the Blazers.<!--When did they pull out?  Did they fold or sell the franchise?-->  In 1978 the [[New Brunswick Hawks]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) were established,<ref name="Sports roundup">{{cite news|title=Sports roundup|date=1978-06-24|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> and were jointly operated by the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]] and the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] as their farm team.<ref name="Sports roundup"/><ref name=newfarm/><ref name=mayget/><ref name=leave/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey notebook Dull Sabres have pundits speculating|date=1982-02-09|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Houston|first=William}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sports roundup|date=1978-07-08|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs, Hawks to Moncton|date=1978-06-20|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  MLGL and the Black Hawks each owned half of the franchise.<ref name=price>{{cite news|title='Everything has price,' Ballard says; it's $50 million for Leafs. Gardens|date=1982-03-31|last=Houston|first=William|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name="Globe and Mail">{{cite news|title=Ballard wants Leafs to have own farm club|date=1980-03-21|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Across Canada: No liquor licence for Leafs-Hawks farm club|date=1978-11-09|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AHL Hawks get Tessier|date=1981-08-22|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  However, by 1980 MLGL had decided that the Leafs needed a team of their own,<ref name="Globe and Mail"/> with a spokesperson citing the limited number of roster spots as the rationale for the move.<ref name=newfarm/><ref name=mayget/>  In 1981 the [[Cincinnati Tigers (ice hockey)|Cincinnati Tigers]] of the old [[Central Hockey League (1963<U+2013>1984)|Central Hockey League]] were established under the ownership of MLGL,<ref name=newfarm>{{cite news|title=Leafs get new farm club in Central Hockey League|date=1981-06-24|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=mayget>{{cite news|title=Cincinnati may get Leaf farm team|date=1981-06-17|last=Campbell|first=Neil|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=price /><ref name=owned/> but the team averaged only 1,500 fans and lost $750,000 in their first season and folded the following spring.<ref name=leave/><ref>{{cite news|title=Salming wins Conacher award Niagara may get Leaf farm team|date=1982-06-11|last=Campbell|first=Neil|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=musicalchairs>{{cite news|title=It's musical chairs on ice as CHL franchises switch|date=1982-05-28|last=Campbell|first=Neil|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  Shortly thereafter, with Chicago having pulled out of New Brunswick in favour of affiliating with the [[Springfield Indians]] on their own,<ref name=leave>{{cite news|title=Leaf team to leave Moncton|date=1982-06-02|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=musicalchairs/> the Leafs relocated the New Brunswick Hawks to [[St. Catharines]], Ontario to establish the [[St. Catharines Saints]] as their farm team.<ref name=owned>{{cite news|title=Leafs place AHL team in St. Kitts|date=1982-06-22|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zmhGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K-kMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1166%2C2190660|title=Red Wings return to North as AHL swells to 13 teams|last=Kane|first=Mike|date=1982-07-24|publisher=[[Schenectady Gazette]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AHL adds three teams in expansion|date=1982-07-24|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  The team played in St. Catharines until 1986, and after stops in [[Newmarket, Ontario]] as the [[Newmarket Saints]] (1986<U+2013>1991) and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]] as the [[St. John's Maple Leafs]] (1991<U+2013>2005), the team moved to Toronto as the [[Toronto Marlies]] (named after the company's former junior team) where they have been playing ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marlies.ca/history/ahl.asp|title=AHL History|accessdate=2014-01-26|publisher=Toronto Marlies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20130404/COLUMN35/104049867/-1/mobile|title=AHL: Bracken Kearns easy Worcester Sharks MVP choice|date=2013-04-04|accessdate=2014-01-26|publisher=[[Telegram & Gazette]]|last=Ballou|first=Bill}}</ref>

The Toronto Marlboros served as a junior farm team for the Maple Leafs for 40 years until direct NHL sponsorship of junior clubs ended in 1967 when the NHL made the [[NHL Entry Draft|Entry Draft]] universal.<ref name=history/><ref name=Hamilton/>  In October 1988, with the team losing hundreds of thousands of dollars a year, MLGL reached an agreement to sell the Marlboros for a reported $500,000, severing their ties with the Maple Leafs.<ref name=Hamilton>{{cite news|title=Hamilton lawyer, realtor purchase OHL Marlboros|first=William|last=Houston|date=1988-10-20|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=newhome>{{cite news|title=Hamilton new home as Marlies are bought|date=1988-10-20|first=Lois|last=Kalchman|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=deathmarlies>{{cite news|title=Death of the Marlies: The cold, hard facts Rising costs and dwindling attendance have sunk once-proud Toronto Marlies, seven- time winners of Memorial Cup|date=1989-03-18|first=Paul|last=Hunter|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=endnears/><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto should miss Marlies, but it won't|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1989-02-08}}</ref> However, the Leafs retained the rights to the Marlies name.<ref name=newhome/><ref name=deathmarlies/><ref name=endnears/>  The OHL team moved to Hamilton for the 1989<U+2013>90 season, becoming the [[Dukes of Hamilton]].<ref name=timeline/><ref name=endnears>{{cite news|title=Marlies fare well as end nears Club on a win streak before transformation to Dukes of Hamilton|date=1989-03-13|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>

===Growth beyond hockey===

In 1967 MLGL entered into negotiations to purchase the financially struggling [[Toronto Maple Leafs (International League)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] baseball team of the minor AAA [[International League]].<ref name=helpinghand>{{cite news|title=Hockey Leafs offer helping hand to struggling baseball namesakes|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1967-08-28}}</ref><ref name=doom/><ref name=notover>{{cite news|title=Game's not over yet for ball Leafs, support grows to keep team here|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1967-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball club gives assurance stadium bill will be paid|last=Dechman|first=Phillip|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1967-11-02}}</ref>  The asking price was $60,000.<ref name=doom/>  The deal ultimately fell apart due to concerns about the team's stadium, [[Maple Leaf Stadium]], which needed up to $250,000 in repairs and whose owner wanted $4 million to purchase it,<ref name=doom>{{cite news|title=Ballard lays Leafs' doom to apathy|date=1967-10-18|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=notover/> and the team was sold and relocated to become the [[Louisville Colonels (minor league baseball)|Louisville Colonels]] for the following season.  MLGL owner Harold Ballard said that the company's interest was due in part to help position itself to go after a [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) franchise for Toronto.<ref name=doom/><ref name=notover/>   In early 1974 MLGL announced plans to build a new baseball stadium in Toronto,<ref>{{cite news|title=East of Yonge near expressway: Free stadium if Metro adopts Ballard's $190 million development|date=1974-01-16|first=Alden|last=Baker|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> but the city ultimately decided to renovate [[Exhibition Stadium]] to make it suitable for baseball.<ref>{{cite news|title=Work could start this fall: Metro votes 23 to 6 to enlarge the CNE Stadium|date=1974-02-27|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Simpson|first=Jeff}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Baseball franchise seekers may pool their resources to expedite stadium plan|date=1974-01-24|first=Jim|last=Vipond|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  At the time, the MLGL group, led by Lorne Duguid, vice-president of [[Hiram Walker]] Distillers and MLGL executive,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gardens will seek baseball franchise|date=1974-11-28|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> was one of at least four bidding for a Toronto MLB team, including competing groups led by [[Labatt Brewing Company]], Robert Hunter, the former President of the International League Maple Leafs, and Canadian Baseball Co, led by Sydney Cooper.<ref name=bothapproached>{{cite news|title=Both major leagues will be approached|date=1974-11-20|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Not a question of money': Godfrey leads Metro delegation seeking major-league franchise|date=1974-10-11|last=Parsons|first=Anne|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=consolidation>{{cite news|title=Franchise consolidation not sighted: Toronto bids likely to fatten price|date=1974-12-04|first=Mary|last=Trueman|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fourth group pursues franchise: As among major baseball clubs sought for Toronto by Labatt|date=1974-11-29|first=Mary|last=Trueman|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  After negotiating with the owners of the [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Chicago White Sox]], [[Cleveland Indians]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Big league baseball asks Ballard to buy team for Toronto|date=1972-03-16|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Jim|last=Proudfoot}}</ref> and [[Oakland Athletics]] in their attempt to acquire a team for Toronto,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard confident Gardens group soon will buy Giants ballclub|date=1975-10-21|first=Don|last=Ramsay|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> MLGL offered $15 million for the [[San Francisco Giants]]<ref>{{cite news|title=2 Toronto-based groups seek franchise at winter baseball meetings in Florida|date=1975-12-04|first=Jim|last=Vipond|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> but the team's owner decided in early 1976 to sell the club to the Labatt group for $13.25 million USD.<ref>{{cite news |title=Giants Moving: Toronto |author= |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |date=1976-01-09|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hbwMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ql8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5064,759147 }}</ref>  While the Giant's relocation was ultimately rejected by a U.S. court,<ref>{{cite web |date=1976-04-04|accessdate=2015-01-02 |title=Will Toronto ever get a baseball franchise? |url=hhttp://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/sports/baseball/major-league-baseball-comes-to-canada/will-toronto-ever-get-a-franchise.html |publisher=[[CBC News]]|first=Suzanne|last=Howden}}</ref> Labatt was awarded an expansion team in the [[American League]] that became the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] for $7 million USD later that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Labatt's, Webster get ball franchise|date=1976-03-27|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|first=Paul|last=Patton}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto Is Given A.L. Franchise|date=1976-03-27|newspaper=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Expansion approved In Eastern Division: Toronto can join American League in 1977|date=1976-03-22|first=Dave|last=Perkins|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>

A team named the [[Toronto Maple Leafs (NLA)|Toronto Maple Leafs]] competed in the inaugural season of the [[National Lacrosse Association]], a professional [[box lacrosse]] league, in 1968 at MLG.<ref name=leafsrespond>{{cite news|title=Leafs respond with win for new coach Kapasky|date=1968-07-18|last=Cauz|first=Louis|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> MLGL owners Ballard and Stafford Smythe were two of the five founding partners of the club,<ref>{{cite news|title=Big gamble by backers in lacrosse|date=1968-04-09|last=Golla|first=James|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> but financial difficulties forced MLGL to take over ownership midway though the season.<ref name=leafsrespond/><ref>{{cite news|title=TV key to lacrosse expansion|date=1968-08-08|first=Terry|last=Fraser|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref><ref name=losesfaith>{{cite news|title=Kells loses faith in sports fans|date=1969-08-14|first=Terry|last=Fraser|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref> The NLA suspended operations prior to the following season.<ref name=losesfaith/><ref>{{cite news|title=Pro lacrosse league suspends operations|date=1969-03-18|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>

[[File:Ivor Wynne Stadium5.jpg|thumb|Ivor Wynne Stadium, home of the Hamilton Tiger-Cats which MLGL owned from the late 1970s to the late 1980s]]

In the early 1970s MLGL announced plans to apply for a second Toronto based [[Canadian Football League]] team, in addition to the [[Toronto Argonauts]], which would play at [[Varsity Stadium]], but the proposal never went anywhere.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bid to CFL for 2nd team in Toronto|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=1973-04-18|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jake Gauaur is waiting for Bill Ballard's cheque|date=1973-04-28|first=Al|last=Sokol|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=linking>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2012/11/20/linking-torontos-football-hockey-pasts|title=Linking Toronto's football, hockey pasts|date=2012-11-20|accessdate=2014-01-14|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Hornby|first=Lance}}</ref>  In 1974, when his former partner [[John Bassett]] put the Argonauts up for sale for $3.3 million, Ballard expressed interest in buying the team, but it was ultimately sold to [[William R. Hodgson]].<ref name=linking/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bassett offers to sell Argos for $3.3 million|date=1974-02-22|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Al|last=Sokol}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bollard wants look at Argo balance sheet before bidding for team|date=1974-02-23|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Cauz|first=Louis}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Barbara and Ballard agree, want to study Argo books|first=Rex|last=MacLeod|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1974-02-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Argo franchise sold to hotel chain owner|date=1974-02-28|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Al|last=Sokol}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Jc3YbqHtsW4C|title=Bassett: John Bassett's forty years in politics, publishing, business and sports|author=[[Maggie Siggins|Siggins, Maggie]]|year=2011}}</ref>  Shortly thereafter Ballard tried to buy the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] of the CFL from owner [[Michael DeGroote]], but this offer was also rejected. Three money-losing seasons later, in February 1978, DeGroote sold the team to MLGL for $1.3 million.<ref name=Hamilton/><ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs' owner Ballard spends $1.3 million to buy the Tiger-Cats|first=Rick|last=Matsumoto|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1978-01-24|pages=B1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Third group says Ticat bid likely if Ballard vetoed|date=1978-02-03|last=Goodman|first=Jeffrey|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= All we need are some players Fans 'choice' for Ticats gleefully takes over team |date=1978-02-17|last=Palango|first=Paul|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=ticats>{{cite web|url=http://ticats.com/page/history_history|title=Tiger-Cats History|accessdate=2014-01-14|publisher=[[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]]}}</ref>  During his tenure as owner of the Tiger-Cats, Ballard repeatedly threatened to move the franchise to Toronto's Varsity Stadium,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ticats talked with Varsity brass|date=1988-11-30|last1=Starkman|first1=Randy|author1link=Randy Starkman|last2=Hunter|first2=Paul|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> which was vetoed by the Argos,<ref>{{cite news|title=Alternative to Tiger-Cats: Bassett sees Hamilton in USFL|date=1983-03-22|first=Marty|last=York|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> and claimed to have lost roughly $20 million over 11 seasons.<ref name=braley>{{cite news|title=Ballard sells Tiger-Cats to Hamilton businessman|date=1989-02-15|publisher=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]}}</ref>   MLGL sold the team in March 1989 to [[David Braley]] for $2.<ref name=ticats/><ref name=braley/><ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard may get more out of $2 Ti-Cat sale|date=1989-11-21|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iM02FnDRZMIC|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|last=Januska|first=Michael|title=Grey Cup Century|year=2012|page=192}}</ref>

Ruby Richman, the former coach of [[Canada men's national basketball team]], working with Ballard pursued a number of existing [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and [[American Basketball Association]] (ABA) teams to relocate to Toronto to play at MLG in the 1970s.<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=nbaawards/><ref name=covetsrockets/> Richman had a tentative agreement to purchase both the [[Miami Floridians]] and [[Pittsburgh Condors]] of the ABA with a plan to merge them into a single Toronto based team, but the deal fell through.<ref name=richmanquest>{{cite news|title=Ruby Richman's quest: The pro basketball chase|date=1976-03-03|last=Fear|first=Jonathan|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> Later, Richman held negotiations with the [[Detroit Pistons]], which were seeking $5 million for the franchise, but pulled out when the price was raised to $8.25 million.<ref name=richmanquest/>  MLGL attempted to purchase and relocate the [[Buffalo Braves]], which had played a number of regular season games at MLG over the years, to Toronto in 1974 for $8.5 million,<ref name=dream>{{cite news|title=Toronto dream of NBA team remains dream|date=1975-01-14|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Snyder rejects Gardens bid of $8.5 million for Braves|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1974-10-05}}</ref> and again several times later,<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=hawks/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bid to bring Braves to Toronto has 50-50 chance|last=Goodman|first=Jeffrey|date=1977-12-14|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VFM_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KVIMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4925,5570645|title=Toronto group seeking Braves|date=1977-12-14|accessdate=2013-10-08|publisher=[[Windsor Star]]}}</ref> but the owners eventually chose to move the team to [[San Diego]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gU4sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=os0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4052,1555484|title=Boston, Buffalo Exchange Owners; Buffalo Transfer to San Diego Approved|date=1978-07-08|accessdate=2013-10-08|publisher=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Nt0hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G0cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4972,3789055|title=Brown now looking west|date=1978-06-23|accessdate=2013-10-08|publisher=[[The Daily News (Kentucky)|Daily News]]}}</ref>  When Toronto was awarded an expansion NBA franchise in 1974 for the 1975<U+2013>76 season<ref name=nbaawards>{{cite news|title=NBA awards expansion franchise to Toronto for 1975<U+2013>76 season|date=1974-06-22|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=withoutowner>{{cite news|title=N.B.A. Adds Toronto, Without Owner|date=1974-06-22|first=Sam|last=Goldaper|newspaper=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=back>{{cite news|title=Toronto is back in NBA picture|last=Keller|first=Arlie|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1975-09-26}}</ref> MLGL was one of three groups to bid for the rights to the team,<ref name=nbaawards/><ref name=withoutowner/><ref>{{cite news|title=Ballard expects to win bid for NBA franchise by end of November|date=1974-11-08|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fresh backing is expected for Toronto's NBA entry|last=Keller|first=Arlie|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1974-12-13}}</ref> but the club never materialized as no group was able to secure funding for the expansion fee of $6.8 million.<ref name=dream/><ref>{{cite news|title=NBA lowers curtain on Toronto's quest for team next season|date=1975-01-15|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Richman seeks NBA backers for Toronto|date=1975-01-08|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> MLGL attempted to purchase and relocate the [[Houston Rockets]] in 1975, which were seeking $8 million for the team, but the team's lease ultimately prevented a relocation.<ref name=richmanquest/><ref name=covetsrockets>{{cite news|title=Ballard covets NBA Rockets, sends Richman to make deal|date=1975-09-25|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rockets' president doubts Ballard to get Houston NBA team|date=1975-09-26|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> In 1976 MLGL attempted to buy the [[Atlanta Hawks]].<ref name=hawks>{{cite news|title=Basketball by this fall is MLG aim|date=1976-06-03|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=back/> In 1979 a Toronto group which included Ballard again pushed for an expansion franchise, but lost out to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto's NBA bid is real longshot|date=1979-02-08|first=Jeffry|last=Goodman|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Roundup: Toronto team may join NBA|date=1979-02-05|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  A Toronto group, which included [[Bill Ballard]], son of Harold, and [[Basketball Hall of Fame]]r [[Wilt Chamberlain]] submitted an application and $100,000 USD deposit for a NBA expansion franchise for MLG in 1986, but of the six cities to apply<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/21/sports/sports-people-toronto-in-nba-bid.html|title=Sports people; Toronto in N.B.A. Bid|date=1986-08-21|accessdate=2014-01-27|publisher=[[New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Toronto investors seek NBA franchise|date=1986-08-20|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|first=James|last=Davidson}}</ref> Toronto was not one of the four which were successful.<ref>{{cite news|title=No NBA club for Toronto|date=1987-04-23|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> It was not until the NBA awarded an expansion franchise to [[John Bitove]], over a group led by future MLSE minority partner [[Larry Tanenbaum]] which had partnered with the Maple Leafs,<ref>{{cite news|title=Leafs left out in cold by NBA decision|last=Shoalts|first=David|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1993-10-01}}</ref> and the [[Toronto Raptors]] joined the NBA for the 1995<U+2013>96 season that the city would get a NBA team.

===Merger with the Raptors and rebranding===
In 1997 it was reported that the Maple Leafs were in negotiations to purchase the [[Toronto Shooting Stars]] of the [[National Professional Soccer League (1984<U+2013>2001)|National Professional Soccer League]].<ref name=hiatus>{{Cite news|title=Shooting Stars to go on hiatus for one season|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1997-08-15|page=E5}}</ref>  The team had been suspended following their inaugural season playing at MLG during which the club lost nearly $1 million and the league was forced to take over operations after only three games when ownership pulled out.<ref name=hiatus/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton in the running for moving Stars|date=1997-03-11|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=League bails out soccer's Stars|first=Norman|last=Da Costa|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1996-11-02|page=E7}}</ref>  However, the team never returned to play.  Following the inaugural season of the [[Hamilton, Ontario]] based [[Ontario Raiders]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] in 1998, in which they lost $250,000 playing at [[Copps Coliseum]], owner [[Chris Fritz]] was forced to look for partners.<ref name=quits>{{cite news|title=Raiders call it quits in Hamilton|date=1998-08-20|last=Kernaghan|first=John|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>  MLSE engaged in negotiations to purchase the team and have it play at MLG.<ref name=quits/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton's pro lacrosse is going, going&nbsp;... |date=1998-07-07|last=Milton|first=Steve|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Three-way toss up for Ontario Raiders|date=1998-07-14|last=Kernaghan|first=John|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>  However, a group which included [[Bill Watters]], the then Assistant General Manager of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]], ultimately bought the team for $250,000 and promptly moved it to MLG where they rebranded the team the [[Toronto Rock]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Watters, Beeston, Domi, Orr bring pro lacrosse to town|date=1998-12-04|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Brown|first=Josh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rock will test Toronto's taste for pro lacrosse|date=1998-12-24|last=Stevens|first=Neil|newspaper=[[Waterloo Region Record]]}}</ref>  MLSE held negotiations with the [[Arena Football League]] in 1998 on acquiring a $4<U+2013>7 million USD expansion franchise for the following season to coincide with the opening of the ACC.<ref name=mayland>{{cite news|title=Arena football team may land in Toronto|date=1998-07-29|last=York|first=Marty|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=CFL is looking at new arenas to keep football alive|date=1999-03-17|last=York|first=Marty|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  The company also submitted an application for a [[Women's National Basketball Association]] franchise, but was rejected by the league due to concerns about their readiness.<ref name=mayland/><ref name=dreamjob>{{cite book|title=Dream Job|last=Peddie|first=Richard|year=2013|publisher=[[Harper Collins]]}}</ref>

[[File:ACC on Bay St and CN Tower.JPG|thumb|left|Air Canada Centre, home to the Maple Leafs and Raptors since 1999, came under the ownership of MLGL while under construction with the merger of the two franchises]]

With MLG aging, MLGL began planning for a new home for the Maple Leafs in the 1990s.  Following years of acrimonious negotiations with the Toronto Raptors on a shared a new arena, MLGL purchased 100% of the basketball club and the arena they had begun constructing, the [[Air Canada Centre]] (ACC), from [[Allan Slaight]] and the [[Bank of Nova Scotia]] on 12 February 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors bought by Leafs|date=1998-02-13|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Deal between Raptors and Leafs has a|date=1998-02-13|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|publisher=[[Canwest]]}}</ref>  MLGL paid a reported $467 million, made up of $179 million for the team and $288 million for the arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stunning deal sees Leafs buy Raptors|date=1998-02-13|publisher=[[Canadian Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NBA approves sale of Raptors|date=1998-03-28|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/28/sports/sp-33649|title= NBA at a Glance / Daily Report|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1998-03-28|accessdate=2014-01-10}}</ref>  [[Richard Peddie]], who had been President of the Toronto Raptors, was retained in the merger and became MLSE's President and CEO.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.uwindsor.ca/alumni/richardpeddie|title=Richard Peddie BComm '70, LLD '01|accessdate=2013-12-27|publisher=[[University of Windsor]]}}</ref>  That July the company adopted a new name, Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment (MLSE), to reflect its broader holdings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hockey Briefs|date=1998-07-16|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  MLSE subsequently ordered major modifications to the original design of the ACC, which was basketball-specific, to make it more suitable for hockey.  Originally planned to cost $217 million, the budget was increased to $265 million after MLSE took control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=1999-02-17|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  MLG was subsequently sold to [[Loblaw Companies]], Canada's largest food retailer, in 2004 for $12 million under the condition that it not be used as a sports and entertainment facility, though MLSE eventually consented to allowing a small arena to be restored in the building to house [[Ryerson University]]'s [[Ryerson Rams|Rams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2011/10/19/maple-leaf-gardens-building-renamed/|title=Maple Leaf Gardens building renamed|last=Chu|first=Showwei|date=2011-10-19|accessdate=2014-01-16|publisher=[[CityNews]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2009/11/30/ryerson_and_loblaws_make_a_deal_for_maple_leaf_gardens.html|title=Ryerson and Loblaws make a deal for Maple Leaf Gardens|date=2009-11-30|accessdate=2014-01-16|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|last= Balkissoon|first= Denise}}</ref>

[[File:Raptors 0607.JPG|thumb|A Raptors game at the Air Canada Centre in 2006 following their acquisition by MLGL]]

The [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) granted MLSE two [[Category 2 specialty channel|category 2]] digital [[specialty channel]] licenses in 2000 for [[Leafs TV]] and [[Raptors NBA TV]], which launched on 7 September 2001.  The channels were used by MLSE to broadcast live games involving their teams in an attempt to increase competition for their rights and drive up the fees paid by other broadcasters.<ref name=dreamjob/>

[[File:Ricohcoliseum.jpg|thumb|left|Ricoh Coliseum after being renovated in 2005 to house MLSE's Toronto Marlies]]

In August 2004 MLSE announced that they would relocate their AHL farm team from [[St. John's, Newfoundland]] to Toronto to play in the [[Ricoh Coliseum]] for the 2005<U+2013>06 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theahl.com/leafs-making-final-run-in-st-john-s-p137005|title=Leafs making final run in St. John's|date=2004-11-29|accessdate=2013-01-03|publisher=[[American Hockey League]]}}</ref> after the arena was left without a hockey tenant following the termination of their lease with the [[Toronto Roadrunners]], the AHL affiliate of the [[Edmonton Oilers]], for defaulting on their rent.<ref name=exboard>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Item%2017-MLSEL.pdf|title=Expansion of MLSEL Office Space in Ricoh Coliseum|date=2013-06-26|accessdate=2014-01-03|publisher=[[Exhibition Place]]}}</ref><ref name=default>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/oilers-farm-team-caught-in-lease-controversy-at-ricoh/article1000820/|title= Oilers' farm team caught in lease controversy at Ricoh |date=2004-06-16|accessdate=2014-01-03|last=Erwin|first=Steve|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|location=Toronto}}</ref>  MLSE agreed to a 20 year lease for the Coliseum,<ref name=exboard/> which had undergone a $38 million renovation in 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/coliseum-gets-makeover/article1009714/|title= Coliseum gets makeover |date=2003-01-16|accessdate=2014-01-02|last=Christie|first=James|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref name=BW>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20031106005775/en/Ricoh-Canada-Announces-Opening-Torontos-Ricoh-Coliseum#.UsZBY_ggp2N|archiveurl=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Ricoh+Canada+Inc.+Announces+the+Opening+of+Toronto%27s+Ricoh+Coliseum.-a0109864185|archivedate=2003-11-06|title=Ricoh Canada Inc. Announces the Opening of Toronto's Ricoh Coliseum.|date=2003-11-06|accessdate=2014-01-02|publisher=[[Business Wire]]}}</ref> that called for rent to cover debt financing charges, property taxes and generate a return to the arena investors,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2013/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-57447.pdf|title=Comprehensive Review of City's Loan Guarantee and Loan Portfolio|date=2013-04-09|accessdate=2014-01-03|publisher=[[City of Toronto]]}}</ref> which exceeds $4 million annually.<ref name=dreamjob/>

[[File:Maple Leaf Square, North Tower.jpg|thumb|Condos at Maple Leaf Square built by a partnership including MLSE next to the Air Canada Centre]]

MLSE announced in April 2005 that they would be working with [[Cadillac Fairview]] (a wholly owned subsidiary of Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan) and Lanterra Developments to build [[Maple Leaf Square]], a major entertainment complex situated next to the ACC. The $500 million {{convert|1700000|sqft|m2}} complex, which was completed in 2010, is a mixed use facility which features the Hotel St. Germain, e11ven restaurant, Real Sports Apparel, Real Sports Bar and Grill, [[Longo's]] grocery store, office space and condominium residences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlse.com/inside_mlse/history.aspx|title=Inside MLSE: History|accessdate=2014-04-06|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Maple-Leaf-Square.aspx|title=Maple Leaf Square|accessdate=2014-04-06|publisher=[[PCL Construction]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/columnists/joe_warmington/2010/10/06/15609141.html|title=Leafs Nation deserves better|first=Joe|last=Warmington|date=2010-10-06|accessdate=2014-04-06|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapleleafsquare.com/home.html|title=Maple Leaf Square|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Square]]|accessdate=2014-04-06|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804001927/http://www.mapleleafsquare.com/home.html|archivedate=2014-08-04}}</ref>  In conjunction with the construction of Maple Leaf Square was a two year, $48 million renovation of the ACC to connect it with the square, which added a new atrium that includes a [[High-definition television|high-definition]] broadcast studio for [[Leafs TV]], [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV Canada]].  The external wall of the atrium features a 30 by {{convert|50|ft|m|sing=on}} video screen which often broadcasts games to spectators gathered in the plaza in front of the arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|date=2009-09-11|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]}}</ref>

[[File:First-goal-at-BMO.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto FC scores their first goal at BMO Field in 2007 following their launch by MLSE]]

[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|Fans watch the Toronto Maple Leafs play the Boston Bruins in game 2 of the Eastern Conference Quarterfinals in the [[2013 Stanley Cup playoffs]] at Maple Leaf Square, a plaza built by MLSE next to the Air Canada Centre]]

===Launch of Toronto FC===

MLSE was awarded a [[Major League Soccer]] expansion team for Toronto, which would become known as [[Toronto FC]], in 2005 for $10 million USD.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/mikeozanian/2013/05/21/david-beckham-to-earn-huge-windfall-from-new-yorks-mls-expansion/|title=David Beckham To Earn Huge Windfall From New York's MLS Expansion|date=2013-05-21|accessdate=2013-11-23|publisher=[[Forbes]]|first=Mike|last=Ozanian}}</ref>  The company also agreed to contribute $8 million towards the construction of Toronto FC's future home [[BMO Field]], which was to cost $62.9 million total, and purchased the naming rights to the stadium for $10 million for 20 years, which they subsequently resold to the [[Bank of Montreal]] for $27 million over the first 10 years.<ref name=approved/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.bmo.com/bmo/files/news%20release/4/1/bmo_bmofieldtor_sep2006_en.htm|title=BMO Field to be Home for Toronto FC and Canada's National Soccer Teams|date=2006-09-20|accessdate=2014-04-27|publisher=[[Bank of Montreal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/695264964/Real-Salt-Lake-negotiating-deal-for-stadium-name-rights.html|title=Real Salt Lake negotiating deal for stadium name rights|date=2008-03-27|accessdate=2014-04-27|first=James|last=Edward|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]}}</ref>  MLSE also agreed to cover any construction cost overruns.<ref name=approved>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/toronto-city-council-approves-soccer-stadium-deal-1.536727|title=Toronto city council approves soccer stadium deal|date=2005-10-27|accessdate=2013-10-01|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/784743/bmo-field-mlse-delivers-financial-return-to-city-of-toronto|title=BMO Field, MLSE delivers financial return to City of Toronto|accessdate=2011-02-23}}</ref> The governments of Canada, Ontario and Toronto contributed $27 million, $8 million and $9.8 million respectively, with the City of Toronto also providing the land.<ref name=approved/><ref name=exboardreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/BMO%20Field-Stadium%20Improvements.pdf|title=Improvements to BMO Field at Exhibition Place|date=2014-03-06|accessdate=2014-03-08|publisher=[[Exhibition Place]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/2005/agendas/council/cc051026/pof9rpt/cl036.pdf|title=Soccer Stadium at Exhibition Place |date= October 2005|accessdate=2013-10-01|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>  In return, MLSE got the management rights for the stadium for 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Soccer/TorontoFC/2009/06/03/pf-9660301.html|title=Grass at BMO remains a contentious issue|date=2009-06-03|last=Sandor|first=Steven|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>  Prior to the 2010 MLS season, MLSE spent $3.5 million to convert the stadium from [[FieldTurf]] to natural grass,<ref name=exboardreport/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2010/03/grass-installation-underway|title=Grass Installation Underway|date=2010-03-29|accessdate=2013-10-01|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]}}</ref> and a further $2 million to expand the north end by 1,400 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2010/03/north-end-expansion-bmo-field|title=North End Expansion Of BMO Field|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]|date=2010-03-18|accessdate=2013-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2010/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-26066.pdf|title=Additional Seating at BMO Field at Exhibition Place|date=2009-12-09|accessdate=2013-11-23|publisher=[[City of Toronto]]}}</ref>  As part of the deal to convert the field to natural grass, MLSE spent $1.2 million adding a winter bubble to [[Lamport Stadium]] and $800,000 building a new artificial turf field to replace the community use hours lost at BMO Field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/grass-bmo-field-attains-final-approval|title=Grass at BMO Field Attains Final Approval|date=2010-01-23|accessdate=2014-01-01|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>

MLSE partnered with Rogers Communications in 2005 to bid to host a regular season [[National Football League]] game [[NFL in Toronto|in Toronto]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Will NFL road show arrive in Toronto?; Godfrey chases regular- season game London the early favourite for 2006|date=2005-09-27|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Byers|first=Jim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=FOOTBALL NFL: Toronto partners pitch to host game|date=2005-10-04|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Grange|first=Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Godfrey buoyed by talks; NFL officials may decide on Toronto quest in weeks Rogers Centre could host game as early as next year|date=2005-10-04|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Byers|first=Jim}}</ref>  On 30 January 2008 it was announced that Rogers and [[Larry Tanenbaum]], chairman of MLSE, had reached an agreement with the [[Buffalo Bills]] to host an annual regular-season and three exhibition NFL games over five seasons at Toronto's [[Rogers Centre]] beginning in 2008, with the games branded the [[Bills Toronto Series]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The breakdown of the Bills' plan to play 8 games in T.O.|date=2008-02-07|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]}}</ref>  At the time MLSE was considering bringing a NFL team to Toronto permanently and building them a new stadium, but abandoned the idea when they concluded that the project would not generate sufficient financial return to justify the significant cost of the project.<ref name=dreamjob/>  Subsequently, MLSE president [[Tim Leiweke]] said on a NFL team in Toronto: "We can't own a team (per NFL rules), but we do have more expertise on how to build (stadiums) than anyone&nbsp;... MLSE can play a role."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/football/2013/11/24/jon_bon_jovi_mlse_give_toronto_inside_track_on_buffalo_bills_kelly.html|title=Jon Bon Jovi, MLSE give Toronto inside track on Buffalo Bills: Kelly|date=2013-11-24|accessdate=2014-01-07|last=Kelly|first=Cathal|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  It has been reported that MLSE is interested in building and managing the proposed NFL stadium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2013/11/25/wheels-quietly-in-motion-to-move-buffalo-bills-to-toronto/|title=Wheels (quietly) in motion to move Buffalo Bills to Toronto|date=2013-11-25|accessdate=2014-01-07|last=Arthur|first=Bruce|publisher=[[National Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2014/07/29/former-sabres-owner-golisano-didnt-submit-bid-to-buy-bills|title=Former Sabres owner Golisano didn<U+2019>t submit bid to buy Bills|date=2014-07-29|accessdate=2014-07-30|first=John|last=Kryk|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> which it has already begun designing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/livin-on-a-prayer-buying-bills-building-new-toronto-stadium-would-be-a-2-billion-play/article15581107/|title=Bon Jovi buying Bills, building new Toronto stadium would be a $2-billion play |date=2013-11-24|accessdate=2014-02-02|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Shoalts|first=David}}</ref>  In 2013 MLSE minority owner Tanenbaum and board member [[Edward Rogers III]] partnered with musician [[Bon Jovi]] to purchase an NFL team.  Following the death of Bills' owner [[Ralph Wilson]] in 2014 the group submitted an offer to purchase the franchise, with speculation that they would move the team to Toronto when their lease permitted it, but were outbid by the [[Terrence Pegula|Pegulas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/sports/source-bon-jovi-group-bid-105-billion-could-have-gone-higher-20140909|title=Source: Bon Jovi group bid $1.05 billion, could have gone higher|publisher=[[Buffalo News]]|first=Tom|last=Precious|date=2014-09-09|accessdate=2014-09-09}}</ref>

The company has contemplated purchasing the Argonauts of the CFL at least twice, with minority partner Tanenbaum keen to add the team to his list of franchises, but concluded that the cost and effort that would be required to make the team profitable was not worth the minimal financial upside.<ref name=dreamjob/><ref name=soon>{{cite web|url=http://www2.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=442375|title=Argonauts could soon be sold to MLSE or Tanenbaum|date=2014-01-28|accessdate=2014-02-02|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref>  In 2013 it was reported that the company was again considering purchasing the team and having them play at a [[#BMO Field renovation|renovated BMO Field]].<ref name=soon/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/09/03/eventual-argos-sale-could-lead-nfl-to-toronto|title=MLSE interested in Argos with eye on NFL in Toronto|date=2013-09-03|accessdate=2014-01-08|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Zicarelli|first=Frank}}</ref><ref name=bigbucks/>  Current Argos owner [[David Braley]] has said that he is having discussions with potential buyers for the team and would like to sell it by his 75th birthday in 2016,<ref name=argos4sale>{{cite web|url=http://metronews.ca/news/vancouver/981787/b-c-lions-not-for-sale-toronto-argos-are-owner-david-braley/|title=B.C. Lions not for sale, Toronto Argonauts are: owner David Braley|date=2014-03-24|accessdate=2014-03-27|publisher=[[Metro International]]|last=Tucker|first=Cam}}</ref> with the asking price reportedly initially $20 million,<ref name=argos4sale/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/22/babcock-deserves-jack-adams-award-more-than-ever|title=Babcock deserves Jack Adams Award more than ever|first=Steve|last=Simmons|authorlink=Steve Simmons|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2014-03-22|accessdate=2014-03-27}}</ref> but since coming down to $10 million.<ref name=spelltrouble>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/07/16/argonauts-off-field-foes-spell-trouble-for-franchise-and-league|title=Argonauts' off-field woes spell trouble for franchise and CFL|first=Bill|last=Lankhof|date=2014-07-16|accessdate=2014-07-19|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>   A vote by MLSE's board on purchasing the team was called in December 2013, but they were unable to come to an agreement on the issue, leading to the possibility that Tanenbaum might purchase the team individually.<ref name=soon/><ref name=shoalts>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/leiweke-outlines-mlse-plans-for-stadium-renovation/article16570810/|title=MLSE outlines plans for stadium renovation, with eye on NFL team |date=2014-01-29|accessdate=2014-02-02|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Shoalts|first=David|location=Toronto}}</ref>  Leiweke has said that "on a stand-alone basis, we have no interest in the Argos. But because of the uniqueness of what we have to go through to get the stadium, we are certainly intertwined. The definition of intertwined is forthcoming."<ref name=bigbucks/>  The potential acquisition of the Argos by MLSE is thought to enhance the likelihood of Toronto receiving an NFL franchise,<ref name=shoalts/> with Peddie saying "everything I'm hearing is that that the NFL is telling them that if you want an NFL team, you better make sure the Argos are okay."<ref name=soon/>  Leiweke has said that moving into a renovated BMO field "will help turn [the Argos] around" and that "there's no way the NFL comes here without the CFL being unbelievably successful first."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/2014/01/28/leiweke_hints_mlse_may_buy_argonauts_with_eyes_on_future_nfl_team.html|title=Leiweke hints bringing Argos to BMO Field could have NFL implications |date=2014-01-28|accessdate=2014-02-02|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Zoe|last=McKnight}}</ref>

When the nearby city of [[Oshawa]] built a new arena, known as [[General Motors Centre]], MLSE was chosen to manage the building.  However, disappointing results in the first year and a half of operations following the arena's opening in November 2006 led MLSE to request that its contract be terminated in March 2008.<ref name=DurhamRegion/>  The company had been attempting to get into the business of managing facilities beyond those where their teams play but decided to withdraw, with Bob Hunter, MLSE's Vice President of venues and entertainment, saying that managing the arena was "no longer a strategic focus for us".<ref name=DurhamRegion>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamregion.com/news-story/3480098-mlse-bows-out-of-management-contract-with-gmc/|title=MLSE bows out of management contract with GMC|date=2008-04-01|accessdate=2014-01-29}}</ref><ref name=OshawaExpress>{{cite news |url=http://www.oshawaexpress.ca/story879.html|title=Global Spectrum takes over GM Centre|first=Jessica|last=Verge|newspaper=The Oshawa Express|date=2008-06-25}}</ref>

===Recent projects===

[[File:Kia training ground.jpg|thumb|KIA Training Ground built by MLSE in the early 2010s to serve as Toronto FC's practice facility and home to the TFC Academy]]

In 2008 MLSE launched the [[TFC Academy]] [[youth system]] to develop soccer players for Toronto FC<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/assets/default/Practice%20Facility.pdf|title=Toronto FC Training Ground and Home of Toronto FC Academy|accessdate=2014-04-10|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref> by taking advantage of MLS's new [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player rule]] which allows clubs to retain the rights to players they develop without them being subject to the [[MLS SuperDraft]].  The senior academy team originally competed in the [[Canadian Soccer League]] until pulling out in early 2013 due to the CSL losing its sanctioning from the [[Canadian Soccer Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canadian-soccer-association-allowed-to-de-sanction-csl-1.1395924|title=Canadian Soccer Association allowed to de-sanction CSL|date=2013-04-23|accessdate=2014-04-10|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mississauga.com/sports-story/3134429-mississauga-eagles-withdraw-from-csl/|title=Mississauga Eagles withdraw from CSL|first=Iain|last=Colpitts|date=2013-04-18|accessdate=2014-04-10}}</ref>  The team played that year in the [[Ontario Soccer League]] before joining [[League1 Ontario]] for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ca/news/4172/canada/2014/04/09/4741589/tfc-academy-joins-new-ontario-semi-pro-league|title=TFC Academy joins new Ontario semi-pro league|date=2014-04-09|accessdate=2014-04-10|first=Rudi|last=Schuller|publisher=[[Goal.com]]}}</ref>  In November 2014 MLSE announced the establishment of their own minor league professional [[Toronto USL Pro team|soccer team]] to play in the [[USL Pro]], which will serve as a [[MLS Reserve League|reserve team]] for TFC and a bridge between the Academy.  The team is set to begin play in the Toronto area in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2014/11/toronto-fc-announces-usl-pro-team |title=Toronto FC announces USL PRO team|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]| date=2014-11-20|accessdate=2014-11-20}}</ref>  In March 2011 [[Downsview Park]] was selected as the site of [[Toronto FC]]'s new state-of-the-art academy and training facility. Construction began on the [[KIA Training Ground]] in May 2011, and the facility opened in June 2012.  It includes three grass fields, one domed turf field and a field house. MLSE spent more than $21 million building the facility and pays rent for the land,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/tfc/2011/10/12/video_tfc_building_permanent_training_facility_at_downsview_park.html|title=Video: TFC building permanent training facility at Downsview Park|date=2011-10-12|accessdate=2014-01-03|last=Girard|first=Daniel|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/trainingground|title=About the facility|accessdate=2014-01-01|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]}}</ref>  In July 2014 it was announced that MLSE would expand the training grounds to house a practice facility for the Argos, which would rent the facility from MLSE and practice on a nearby city owned field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.argonauts.ca/article/argos-partner-with-mlse-to-build-new-practice-facility|title=Argos partner with MLSE to build new practice facility|date=2014-07-24|accessdate=2014-07-24|publisher=[[Toronto Argonauts]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/argos/2014/07/24/argos_maple_leafs_sports_and_entertainment_partner_on_new_practice_facility.html|title=Argonauts, MLSE partner on new practice facility|date=2014-07-25|accessdate=2014-07-25|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Josh|last=Rubin}}</ref>  The team moved in that September.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/09/09/new-practice-facility-gives-argonauts-some-stability|title=New practice facility gives Argonauts some stability|date=2014-09-09|accessdate=2014-09-09|first=Frank|last=Zicarelli|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>

Then Raptors President and General Manager [[Bryan Colangelo]] said in 2008 that MLSE was considering launching a [[NBA Development League]] franchise in the Toronto area within the next couple of years to serve as a developmental team for the Raptors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2008/01/15/dleague_coming_to_to.html|title=D-League coming to T.O.?|date=2008-01-15|accessdate=2014-08-05|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Doug|last=Smith}}</ref>  [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]]'s [[Copps Coliseum]] as well as [[Oshawa]] were reportedly the two cities under consideration to host the franchise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thespec.com/article/310148|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113141026/http://www.thespec.com/article/310148|title=Hey, it ain't the NBA ... But Raptors placing a D-League farm team in Copps will draw drafted players|date=2008-01-16|archivedate=2009-12-18|newspaper=[[Hamilton Spectator]]|first=Scott|last=Radley}}</ref>  In 2014 his replacement, [[Masai Ujiri]], reiterated that the company was interested in purchasing a D-League franchise to play close to Toronto within the next few years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/09/29/toronto-raptors-coachs-number-one-goal-is-to-defend-division-title/|title=Toronto Raptors coach sets sights on defending division title: <U+2018>That<U+2019>s our number one goal<U+2019>|date=2014-09-29|accessdate=2014-10-25|last=Koreen|first=Eric|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref>

It was announced on 23 January 2009 that MLSE would acquire [[Insight Sports]]' 80.1% interest in [[GolTV (Canada)|GolTV Canada]], a digital cable channel devoted to soccer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.highbeam.com/1758/article-1G1-192490992/mlse-acquires-goltv-insight-sports|title= MLSE acquires GolTV from Insight Sports.|date=2009-01-23|accessdate=2014-04-05|publisher=[[CNW Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/tfc-gets-new-family-member|title=TFC gets new family member|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]}}</ref>  In November 2009 MLSE applied to the CRTC for a Category 2 digital TV license for a general interest sports service provisionally named Mainstream Sports,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2009/2009-803.htm#9|title=Broadcasting Notice of Consultation CRTC 2009-803|date=2009-12-23|accessdate=2014-01-11|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref> which was granted in June 2010.<ref name=msscrtc>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2010/2010-395.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2010-395|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|date=2011-06-18|accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> MLSE planned to broadcast its teams' games on the channel, along the lines of team-owned [[regional sports network]]s in the United States such as [[YES Network]] and the [[New England Sports Network]], with the tentative name "Real Sports" (in keeping with the branding of MLSE's sports bar and apparel store).<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/david-shoalts/whats-next-for-mlse/article2251448/|title=What's next for MLSE?|first=David|last=Shoalts|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2011-11-28|accessdate=2011-12-10|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/2011/11/27/maple_leaf_sports_plans_broadcast_gamble.html|title=Maple Leaf Sports plans broadcast gamble|first=Rick|last=Westhead|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2011-11-27|accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref> It was never revealed whether the channel would have replaced, or supplemented, MLSE's existing digital channels.  Peddie credited the threat of a Real Sports channel as a motivator for Rogers and Bell, owners of sports channels [[Sportsnet]] and [[The Sports Network|TSN]] respectively, to purchase the company due to concerns about losing the rights to broadcast MLSE teams to the channel or having to pay huge fees for them.<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/business/2013/10/22/leafs_nba_gol_tv_hidden_key_to_mlse_value_richard_peddie_says.html|title=Leafs, NBA, GOL TV, hidden key to MLSE value, Richard Peddie says|date=2013-10-22|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  The acquisition of MLSE by Rogers and Bell in 2012, and associated agreements to divide the company's regional broadcast rights between the two, eliminated the need for the channel<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/allure-of-certainty-makes-partners-out-of-rivals-rogers-bce/article2266649/|title=Allure of certainty makes partners out of rivals Rogers, BCE|first=Susan|last=Krashinsky|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2011-12-10|accessdate=2011-12-10|quote=It also prevents the launch of a well-connected competitor. MLSE has a broadcast licence for a 'specialty' cable sports channel <U+2013> tentatively named Real Sports, according to sources <U+2013> that could have snatched away those games once the deals with Sportsnet and TSN had expired.|location=Toronto}}</ref> and its license expired after the three year deadline for launch passed in 2013.<ref name=msscrtc/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/ownership/eng/cht177.pdf|title=Maple Leafs & Raptors|date=2014-03-12|accessdate=2014-04-05|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]}}</ref>

In September 2009 the Maple Leafs and Marlies opened their new hockey practice facility, the [[MasterCard Centre]].<ref name=nowopen>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=497918|title=Leafs New Practice Rink Unveiled On Tuesday|date=2009-09-08|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  The arena was a joint venture between MLSE, the [[City of Toronto]] and the [[Lions Club|Lakeshore Lions Club]] to replace the nearby [[Lakeshore Lions Arena]],<ref name=cadillac>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/hockey/2009/09/09/10798796-sun.html|title=Leafs open 'Cadillac' of practice facilities|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]|last=Hornby|first=Lance|date=2009-09-08|accessdate=2011-05-06}}</ref> and was built at a cost of $44 million, after cost overruns drove up the cost from $33.65 million.<ref name=takeover>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2011/06/13/city_poised_to_take_over_arenas_40_million_debt.html|title=City poised to take over arena's $40 million debt|date=2011-06-13|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Moloney|first=Paul}}</ref><ref name=guar/><ref name=stink/>  The Lions Club contributed $40 million to the project, with the city providing a $35.5 million loan guarantee.<ref name=guar>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/20/torontos-449-million-loan-groan|title=Toronto's $449-million loan groan|last=Levy|first=Sue-Ann|date=2011-06-20|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=stink>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/13/rink-stink|title=Rink stink|last=Levy|first=Sue-Ann|date=2011-06-11|accessdate=2011-01-06|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=onhook>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/toronto-taxpayers-on-hook-as-lakeshore-arena-runs-out-of-cash/article2058581/|title= Toronto taxpayers on hook as Lakeshore arena runs out of cash|date=2011-06-13|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Church|first=Elizabeth}}</ref><ref name=whatwrong>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2011/06/25/what_went_wrong_with_etobicokes_stateoftheart_arena.html|title=What went wrong with Etobicoke's state-of-the-art arena?|date=2011-06-25|accessdate=2014-01-06|last=Doolittle|first=Robyn|authorlink=Robyn Doolittle|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>  The [[Toronto District School Board]] leased the land for the arena to the Lakeshore Lions for a 50 year term.<ref name=onhook/>  MLSE spent a further $5 million on training and medical facilities,<ref name=nowopen/><ref name=cadillac/> and pays $600,000 annually to rent the building.<ref name=nowopen/><ref name=cadillac/>  The arena was originally operated by the Lakeshore Lions Club,<ref name=teamup>{{cite web|url=http://www.mastercard.com/ca/company/en/press/2009/08_19_hockey_excellence.html|title=Leafs, Marlies, Lakeshore Lions Club Team up with MasterCard To Foster Hockey Excellence|date=2009-08-19|accessdate=2004-01-06|publisher=[[MasterCard]]}}</ref> but in June 2011, with the arena on the verge of defaulting on its rising debt, the City of Toronto took control and assumed its $43.4 million debt<ref name=guar/><ref name=stink/><ref name=onhook/><ref name=annualreport>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2012/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-50421.pdf|title=Annual Report 2011|year=2011|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=Lakeshore Arena Corporation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/06/20/bailout-for-lakeshore-lions-arena-approved|title=Bailout for Lakeshore Lions arena approved|date=2011-06-20|accessdate=2014-01-06|last=Peat|first=Don|publisher=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref>  with the intention to return it to private management within 2<U+2013>3 years.<ref name=takeover/><ref name=guar/><ref name=onhook/><ref name=annualreport/><ref name=financialstatement>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2013/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-58245.pdf|title=RE: Lakeshore Arena Corporation 2012 Audited Financial Statements and Annual Report of the Board of Directors|date=2013-03-31|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=Lakeshore Arena Corporation}}</ref>  A city councillor has suggested that MLSE, which operates BMO Field and Ricoh Coliseum on behalf of the city, would be "the logical party" to take over the arena, and a spokesperson for the company said "while we don't have any interest in purchasing the facility, we are open to discussing the possibility of managing the facility on behalf of the City".<ref name=takeover/>  MLSE's executive vice president of venues and entertainment Bob Hunter confirmed that they would bid for the right to run the building.<ref name=whatwrong/>

At one point MLSE contemplated purchasing the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] of MLB and [[Sportsnet]] from [[Rogers Communications]], but concerns about the viability of [[SkyDome]] as a baseball venue and the profitability of the team resulted in the company not pursuing either.<ref name=dreamjob/>  The company also considered investing in an English soccer club,<ref name=dreamjob/><ref>{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=Leafs owner eyes U.K. soccer|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/2008/04/24/leafs_owner_eyes_uk_soccer.html|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2008-04-24|accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref> and on 29 May 2012, after the [[Leeds United]] Supporters Trust put out a request for a takeover from majority shareholder [[Ken Bates]], it was reported that MLSE were in talks to buy the team. However, the company later denied that it planned to purchase the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-in-takeover-talks-with-investors-updated-1-4594092|title=Leeds United in takeover talks with investors UPDATED|first=Phil|last=Hay|work=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=2012-05-29|accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref>

Peddie retired as President and CEO of MLSE at the end of 2011 after fourteen years on the job,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/2012/01/08/feschuk_newly_retired_peddie_muses_on_life_after_mlse.html|title=Newly retired Peddie muses on life after MLSE|last=Feschuk|first=Dave|date=2012-01-08|accessdate=2013-12-17|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.uwindsor.ca/ols/2013/speakers/richard-peddie-2013|title=Richard Peddie|accessdate=2013-12-27|publisher=[[University of Windsor]]}}</ref> having tripled the value of the company.<ref name=isnteverything/>  However, he was often criticized for his inability to end the company's long championship drought.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/what-to-make-of-peddies-legacy-with-mlse/|title=What to make of Peddie's legacy with MLSE?|date=2013-10-21|accessdate=2014-07-03|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>  Of the three major franchises the company currently owns (Maple Leafs, Raptors and Toronto FC), only the Maple Leafs have ever won a championship, and not since their [[1967 Stanley Cup Finals|1967 Stanley Cup]].  The only other major championship MLSE has won was the [[74th Grey Cup]] in 1986 by the Tiger-Cats.  Though [[Tom Anselmi]] briefly took over as President,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/2013/07/24/tim_leiweke_shakes_up_mlse_corporate_structure.html | title=Tim Leiweke shakes up MLSE corporate structure|date=2013-07-24|accessdate=2014-07-03|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> he was replaced in June 2013 by high profile executive [[Tim Leiweke]] who had previously run [[Anschutz Entertainment Group]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/apr/27/sports/la-sp-0427-tim-leiweke-20130427|title=Tim Leiweke tapped to lead Canadian sports conglomerate|last=Elliot|first=Helene|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=2013-04-27|accessdate=2014-07-03}}</ref>  On 21 August 2014 Leiweke announced that he was stepping down, but would remain in his position until 30 June 2015 or until a successor is appointed.<ref name=Leiweke2015>{{Cite news|url = http://sports.nationalpost.com/2014/08/21/tim-leiweke-set-to-step-down-from-mlse-to-pursue-other-opportunities/|title = Tim Leiweke set to step down from MLSE to pursue other opportunities|last = Fitz-Gerald|first = Sean|date = 2014-08-21|accessdate=2014-08-21|newspaper = [[National Post]]}}</ref>

