==Proposed projects==

===BMO Field renovation===
{{main|BMO Field#Renovation}}
[[File:BMO Field in 2009.jpg|thumb|BMO Field in 2009]]
The financial success of Toronto FC led MLSE to undertake a $105 million renovation to BMO Field.<ref name=bmoexpansion>{{cite web|url=http://bmofield.com/expansion/|title=BMO Field Expansion|publisher=BMO Field|accessdate=2014-10-11}}</ref>  Under a two phase process, the stadium's capacity will be increased from 21,566 to 30,000 by 1 May 2015 for $65 million, and a canopy roof covering most permanent seating areas added by 1 May 2016 for $40 million.<ref name=bmoexpansion/><ref name=cityamend/>

The City of Toronto, which owns the facility, originally insisted that any renovations allow for the Argonauts, who must vacate their current home [[Rogers Centre]] by the end of 2017 season, to move in.<ref name=bigbucks>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/16/mlse-plans-to-spend-big-bucks-to-upgrade-bmo-field|title=MLSE plans to spend big bucks to upgrade BMO Field|last=Larson|first=Kurtis|date=2014-03-16|accessdate=2014-03-16|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=makeover/><ref name=citypushing>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2014/03/07/mlse_city_pushing_to_move_argos_to_bmo_field.html|title=MLSE: City pushing to move Argos to BMO Field|date=2014-03-07|accessdate=2014-03-08|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=excomrep/>  The original plans called for retractable endzone seating so that the pitch can be lengthened to fit a [[Canadian football]] field with 25,000 seats, and the possibility to temporarily expand capacity to 40,000 for big events<ref name=loi>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-67468.pdf|title=Proposal for Expansion of Stadium at Exhibition Place|date=2014-03-10|accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref> such as [[rugby sevens]] at the 2015 Pan-Am games, the 2018 [[NHL Winter Classic]], [[Grey Cup]]s, [[MLS Cup]]s or a successful [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] bid by Canada.<ref name=bigbucks/><ref name=makeover/><ref name=excomrep/><ref name=paidback>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/01/19/mlses_leiweke_taxpayers_would_be_paid_back_for_bmo_field_expansion.html|title=MLSE's Leiweke: Taxpayers would be paid back for BMO Field expansion|first=Daniel|last=Dale|date=2014-01-19|accessdate=2014-04-20|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=plans>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/2014_0305%20BMO%20Field%20-%20Public%20Meeting_FINAL.pdf|title=BMO Field - Public Meeting|date=2014-03-05|accessdate=2014-03-08|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/24-7/winter-classic-could-be-coming-to-toronto/|title=Toronto could host Winter Classic in 2017|date=2013-12-31|accessdate=2014-01-03|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>

MLSE sought $10 million in funding from each of the City, Provincial Government, and Federal Government to top up their $90 million contribution, plus any cost overruns, to the project.<ref name=makeover>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2014/03/14/mlse_wants_10_million_from_toronto_for_bmo_field_makeover.html|title=MLSE wants $10 million from Toronto for BMO Field makeover|date=2014-03-14|accessdate=2014-03-16|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Tepper|first=Sean}}</ref><ref name=excomrep>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-67466.pdf|title=Renovation and Expansion of BMO Field|date=2014-03-05|accessdate=2014-03-15|publisher=[[City of Toronto]]}}</ref><ref name=loi/><ref name=kelly>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/14/norm-kelly-wants-city-to-advance-mlse-10-million-for-bmo-improvements|title=Norm Kelly wants city to advance MLSE $10 million for BMO improvements|last=Peat|first=Dan|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2014-03-14|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/03/12/mayor-rob-fords-pay-freeze-request-goes-to-executive-committee|title=Mayor Rob Ford's pay freeze request goes to executive committee|last=Peat|first=Dan|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2014-03-12|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>  In return, they will pay annual rent to the City for the upgraded stadium,<ref name=excomrep/><ref name=loi/> while their management and naming rights agreements for the stadium, which were set to expire in 2027, were extended by 10 years.<ref name=excomrep/><ref name=loi/>  The [[Toronto City Council]] approved the project in June 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2014.MM52.28|title=Tracking Status|date=2014-06-10|accessdate=2014-06-11|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>  However, with deadlines approaching to start construction to ensure that the stadium would be ready for the 2015 Pan-Am games, and no funding commitments from either the federal or provincial governments, MLSE decided to move forward with the first phase of renovations without securing the remaining $20 million in funding.<ref name=notclosing>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2014/05/27/mlse-boss-leiweke-said-or_n_5400443.html|title=MLSE boss Leiweke said organization not closing door on Argos at BMO Field|first=Dan|last=Ralph|date=2014-05-27|accessdate=2014-05-27|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref><ref name=argosout>{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/argos-on-the-outs-in-bmo-field-dispute-between-mlse-and-federal-government/article18862832/|title=Argos on the outs in BMO Field dispute between MLSE and federal government|date=2014-05-27|accessdate=2014-05-27|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|last1=Kelly|first1=Cathal|last2=Curry|first2=Bill}}</ref>  Lengthening of the field and the infrastructure to allow for temporarily increasing seating capacity was postponed to a third phase costing $20<U+2013>25 million to be completed by 1 May 2017, pending the $20 million funding gap being filled.<ref name=cityamend>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/mm/bgrd/backgroundfile-70433.pdf|title=Draft Amended and Restated Letter of Intent from Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment Ltd|date=June 2014|accessdate=2014-06-11|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref><ref name=notclosing/><ref name=argosout/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/argos/2014/05/27/argonauts_move_to_bmo_field_on_hold_mlse_says.html|title=Argonauts' move to BMO Field 'on hold,' MLSE says|first=Daniel|last=Dale|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=2014-05-27|accessdate=2014-05-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/football/cfl/pity-toronto-as-it-allows-storied-argos-to-vanish/|title=Pity Toronto as it allows storied Argos to vanish|first=Michael|last=Grange|date=2014-09-16|accessdate=2014-10-11|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref>  The official groundbreaking took place on September 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontofc.ca/news/2014/09/bmo-field-renovation-officially-underway|title=BMO Field Renovation Officially Underway|date=2014-09-23|accessdate=2014-10-11|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1578582/bmo-field-expansion-construction-begins/|title=BMO Field expansion construction begins|date=2014-09-23|accessdate=2014-10-11|publisher=[[Global News]]}}</ref>

===Raptors practice facility===
In November 2013 it was reported that MLSE had contracted an architect to design a new practice facility for the Raptors.<ref name=rapspractice>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2013/11/11/Facilities/Breaking-Ground.aspx|title=MLSE hires designer for practice facility; downtown targeted |date=2013-11-11|accessdate=2014-01-06|last=Muret|first=Don}}</ref>  The team has trained on a practice court located in the ACC since its opening in 1999, and a new facility would allow this space to be repurposed into a restaurant or nightclub.<ref name=rapspractice/><ref name=announcepract/>  The facility, which is planned to be built at [[Exhibition Place]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/07/29/raptors-in-talks-for-exhibition-place-practice-facility|title=Raptors in talks for Exhibition Place practice facility|first=Don|last=Peat|date=2014-07-29|accessdate=2014-07-29|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> will feature two courts, one of which will be open to the public.<ref name=rapsloi/><ref name=notslamdunk>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/4755248-new-raptors-practice-facility-at-exhibition-place-still-not-a-slam-dunk/|title=New Raptors practice facility at Exhibition Place still not a slam-dunk|date=2014-08-12|accessdate=2014-08-16|first=Hilary|last=Caton|publisher=Inside Toronto}}</ref>  [[Canada Basketball]] will also use the facility.<ref name=notslamdunk/><ref name=MLSEppt/>  MLSE will pay the entire $30 million construction cost and lease the property from the city for $205,000 annually, subject to reassessments for inflation, for a 20 year term, with two options to extend it by a further 10 years, following which the city would take ownership of the building.<ref name=rapsloi/><ref name=btcproposal/>  MLSE has requested that the city exempt the portion of the facility that is available to the public (32%) from city taxes.<ref name=rapsloi/><ref name=btcproposal>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-72768.pdf|title=Proposed Basketball Training Centre at Exhibition Place|date=2014-08-06|accessdate=2014-08-17|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>  Construction is scheduled to begin in November 2014,<ref name=rapsloi>{{cite web|url=http://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2014/ex/bgrd/backgroundfile-72809.pdf|title=Appendix A|date=August 2014|accessdate=2014-08-20|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref><ref name=notslamdunk/> to have the facility completed in time for the team's hosting of the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game|NBA All-Star Game]] in February 2016.<ref name=announcepract>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/04/16/raptors-close-to-making-announcement-on-new-practice-court|title=Raptors close to making announcement on new practice court|first=Ryan|last=Wolstat|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2014-04-16|accessdate=2014-04-16}}</ref><ref name=MLSEppt>{{cite web|url=http://www.explace.on.ca/database/rte/files/Raptors%20Training-PP-MLSE.pdf|title=High performance basketball development and training centre|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports + Entertainment|accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref> The proposal was approved by the Board of Governors of Exhibition Place on August 14,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/15/cne-is-forced-to-change-with-the-landscape|title=CNE is forced to change with the landscape|first=Joe|last=Warmington|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=2014-08-15|accessdate=2014-08-16}}</ref> the Executive Committee of the City of Toronto on August 20,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/basketball/raptors-exhibition-place-plan-scores-victory-at-toronto-city-hall/article20134057/|title=Raptors<U+2019> Exhibition Place plan scores victory at Toronto city hall|first=Elizabeth|last=Church|date=2014-08-20|accessdate=2014-08-22|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2014/08/20/executive_committee_approves_plan_for_raptors_training_centre_at_exhibition_place.html|title=Executive committee approves plan for Raptors training centre at Exhibition Place|first=Paul|last=Moloney|date=2014-08-20|accessdate=2014-08-22|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> and the Toronto City Council on August 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2014/08/25/mayor-rob-ford-fuming-after-raptors-facility-approved|title=Mayor Rob Ford rips Raptors facility approval|date=2014-08-25|accessdate=2014-09-01|first=Don|last=Peat|newspaper=[[Toronto Sun]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/new-raptors-training-centre-approved-by-toronto-council-1.2746164|title=New Raptors training centre approved by Toronto council|date=2014-08-25|accessdate=2014-09-01|publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2014.EX44.3|title=Proposed Basketball Training Centre at Exhibition Place|accessdate=2014-08-16|publisher=City of Toronto}}</ref>

==Ownership==

===Conn Smythe===
[[File:Conn smythe.jpg|thumb|Conn Smythe, founder of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]

Although Conn Smythe was the face of MLGL from its founding in 1931, he did not acquire majority ownership of the company until 1947, following a power struggle between directors who supported him as president and those who wanted him replaced with [[Frank J. Selke]]. With the help of a $300,000 loan from Toronto stockbroker and MLGL shareholder [[Percy Gardiner]], and the support of minority partner Jack Bickell, Smythe was able to buy 30,000 shares in MLGL from Gardiner<ref name=powerplay>{{cite news|title=Gardens power plays|date=1995-04-03|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> and installed himself as president on 19 November 1947, replacing  Edward Bickle.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baseball's bankroll gone |last=Dunnell|first=Milt|authorlink=Milt Dunnell|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1965-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hunter |first=Douglas |year=1997 |title=Champions: The Illustrated History of Hockey's Greatest Dynasties. |location=Chicago, Illinois |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=1-57243-213-6 |page=50}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Smythe is elected Gardens' president|date=1947-11-20|newspaper=[[Toronto Daily Star]]}}</ref>  The loan was paid off in 1960.<ref>{{cite book |title=Centre Ice: The Smythe Family, the Gardens, and the Toronto Maple Leafs Hockey Club |last1=Smythe |first1=Thomas Stafford |last2=Shea |first2=Kevin Shea |publisher=Fenn Publishing Co. |year=2000 |location=Bolton, Ontario, Canada |isbn=1-55168-250-8 |ref=harv|pages=156<U+2013>167}}</ref>  In November 1961 Smythe sold 45,000 of his 50,000 shares to a three-person partnership formed by [[Stafford Smythe]] (Conn Smythe's son), [[Harold Ballard]] and [[John Bassett]], who at the time owned part of the [[Toronto Argonauts]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] and [[Toronto Telegram]], for $2.3 million.  When combined with their own holdings, this gave them 87,000 shares representing 60% of the company.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217}}<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death>{{cite news|title=Ballard's death laid groundwork|date=2010-12-01|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref name=bassettsells/>  Ballard fronted Stafford most of the money for the purchase though a loan he obtained.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=shakeup>{{cite news|title=Ballard president in shakeup at Gardens|last=Beddoes|first=Dick|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1971-10-21}}</ref>  According to several sources, Conn thought the sale was only to his son,<ref name=thoughages/> and was furious when he learned that Ballard and Bassett were his partners. He had hoped that Stafford would keep MLGL for his son, Tommy.<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|217<U+2013>218}}  However, it is unlikely that Stafford could have raised the millions needed for the deal on his own.  Stafford became president of MLGL and governor of the Maple Leafs, with Ballard executive vice president and Bassett chairman of the board.<ref name=powerplay/>

===Harold Ballard, John Bassett and Stafford Smythe===
In March 1966 Conn sold his remaining shares and resigned from the board of directors after a [[Muhammad Ali]] boxing match was scheduled for MLG. He found Ali's refusal to serve in the U.S. Army in the [[Vietnam War]] to be offensive,<ref name=smytheyoung/>{{rp|232}} and said that by accepting the fight, MLGL owners had "put cash ahead of class."<ref>{{cite news |title='Cash rated over class' Conn quits |author=McKee, Ken |work=Toronto Star |date=1966-03-08}}</ref>  Within three years under the new owners, profits at MLGL had tripled to just under $1 million. Ballard negotiated lucrative deals to place advertising throughout the building, and greatly increased the number of seats in the arena.<ref>''Ballard: A Portrait of Canada's Most Controversial Sports Figure'', William Houston, Summerhill Press, 1984, p. 60.</ref>

Following a [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] raid at MLG in 1968, Stafford was charged with income tax evasion, and he and Ballard were accused of illegally taking money from MLGL to pay for renovations of their houses and other personal expenses.  Just before the charges were laid, Bassett argued to the board that Stafford and Ballard should be removed from their posts. Following an 8<U+2013>7 vote of the board of directors on 26 June 1969, Stafford and Ballard were both fired, and Bassett was appointed president of MLGL. However, Bassett did not force Stafford and Ballard to sell their shares, and both men remained on the board.  This proved to be a serious strategic blunder; Stafford was the largest single shareholder in MLGL, and he and Ballard controlled almost half the company's stock between them.  They were thus able to regain control of the board in 1970 and Stafford was once again appointed president.<ref name=powerplay/>  Facing an untenable situation, Bassett sold the 196,200 shares he controlled in MLGL to Stafford and Ballard in September 1971 for $5.4 million, which he used to buy out his partners in the Argos.<ref name=death/><ref name=bassettsells>{{cite news|title=Bassett sells Gardens stock, buys control of Argos|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=1971-09-02|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref name=shakeup/> Combined with their 306,295 jointly controlled shares, the transaction gave the Stafford Smythe-Ballard partnership 78% of the stock.<ref name=bassettsells/><ref name=shakeup/>  Ballard would be convicted of 47 charges<ref name=howherold/> and sentenced to three years in a federal penitentiary, but Stafford died in October 1971 of a bleeding ulcer at the age of only 50 just before his trial was scheduled to begin.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/>  Under the terms of Stafford's will, of which Ballard was an [[executor]],<ref name=repeats>{{cite news|title=History repeats itself&nbsp;... almost|date=1999-03-22|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref> each partner was allowed to buy the other's shares upon their death.  Stafford's brother and son tried to keep the shares within the family,<ref>{{cite news|title=MLG control at stake: Smythe bid for Ballard stock rejected|first=Dick|last=Beddoes|authorlink=Dick Beddoes|date=1972-01-05|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> but in February 1972 Ballard bought all 251,545 of Stafford's shares for $7.5 million, valuing the company at $22 million.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=death/><ref name=rinkrat/><ref name=buyscontrol/><ref name=gardensprez/>  Stafford's brother Hugh also sold his shares to Ballard, ending the Smythe family's 45-year involvement in the company.  Combined with Ballard's 262,162 shares, this gave him majority ownership of about 70%.<ref name=rinkrat>{{cite news|title=Harrold Ballard: From rink rat to Gardens' boss|date=1972-02-05|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Orr|first=Frank}}</ref><ref name=buyscontrol>{{cite news|title=Ballard buys Gardens control for $7,546,350|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1972-02-04|first=Milt|last=Dunnell|authorlink=Milt Dunnell}}</ref><ref name=gardensprez>{{cite news|title=Gardens' president Harold Ballard to buy Smythe shares|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=1972-02-05|last=Lutsky|first=Irvin}}</ref>

===Harold Ballard===
In 1966 Ballard set up a family [[holding company]], named Harold E. Ballard Ltd. (HEBL), for his assets including his shares in MLGL as part of an [[estate freeze]].<ref name=assulttrial>{{cite news|title=Son of a Ballard: Assault trial a rehearsal for family fight for fortune|date=1989-09-23|last=McDonald|first=Archie|newspaper=[[Vancouver Sun]]}}</ref><ref name=follies>{{cite news|title=The Maple Leaf Follies: Who needs hockey? With a team of lawyers fighting for ambitious corporations and the feuding Ballard clan, nothing can compare with the faceoff for Maple Leaf Gardens|newspaper=[[Financial Post]]|date=1991-10-01|last=Johnson|first=Arthur}}</ref>  Ballard distributed 103 [[common shares]] in HEBL, with his three children, Bill, Harold Jr., and Mary Elizabeth, each receiving 34 which were held in [[Trust law|trust]], and his wife Dorothy receiving 1, which Harold would inherit upon her death three years later.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=familyaffair>{{cite news|title=Ballard money a family affair Daughter gets $15.5 million as Harold buys her shares|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1989-01-25}}</ref><ref name=missdeadline/>  Harold retained 308,000 [[preferred shares]] in HEBL.<ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing>{{cite news|title=Faceoff brewing over Ballard's fortune|last=Hurst|first=Lynda|newspaper=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=1990-02-25}}</ref>  While the equity of the company was vested in the common stock, both common and preferred shares each received a single vote, ensuring that Harold retained control of the company.<ref name=follies/>

After getting into financial difficulty, Harold reached an agreement with [[Molson Brewery]] in November 1980, which at the time owned the [[Montreal Canadiens]], for the company to cover his debt financing charges on a loan of $8.8 million for 10 years in exchange for an option to purchase a 19.9% block of shares in MLGL from HEBL and a right of first refusal on the rest of HEBL's shares.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=molsonnets/><ref name=molsonpurchase/>  The NHL did not learn of the deal until the late 1980s.<ref name=molsonnets/>  In 1982 he offered to sell the company for $50 million, with the arena alone reportedly valued at $11 million, though a stockholders' report the following year placed the value of MLGL at $23.5 million.<ref name=bigmoney/><ref name=price/>  When Harold transferred ownership of his personal real estate holdings, which were valued at $2.52 million, to HEBL in January 1989, he acquired 4 newly issued common shares in the company plus a promise of a further $896,472 rather than cash.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=follies/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/>  Mary Elizabeth sold her stake in HEBL to her father for $15.5 million in January 1989,<ref name=familyaffair/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> after originally having a deal to sell the stake to Don Giffin,<ref name=follies/> while Harold Jr. sold his back to HEBL for $21 million in June of the same year.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=follies/><ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/>  Harold secured a loan from Molson for the full amount of his buyout of Mary Elizabeth, using the 34 acquired shares in HEBL as security.<ref name=missdeadline>{{cite news|title=Harold E. Ballard Ltd. misses Molson loan deadline|date=1991-01-03|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref>  Harold Jr.'s shares were subsequently retired.<ref name=faceoffbrewing/>  Bill sued his father for $170 million over HEBL's acquisition of Harold Jr.'s stake,<ref name=assulttrial/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/> claiming that he and partner [[Michael Cohl]] had acquired a right of first refusal to purchase the shares for $20 million that February.<ref name=powerplay/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/>  Shortly thereafter, HEBL issued Harold 32 common shares and $125,216 in exchange for ownership of his 350,200 personally held MLGL shares and $125,000.<ref name=howherold/><ref name=faceoffbrewing/>  Two more new common shares would be granted to Harold to repay the $911,000 debt HEBL owed him from his two transactions with the company.<ref name=howherold/>  This gave Harold, who feared that Bill was positioning himself to take over the holding company, control of HEBL.<ref name=powerplay/>  Harold did not want his bickering children to inherit MLGL because he feared they would destroy it.<ref name=howherold>{{cite news|title=How Harold Ballard got the Gardens|last=Tyler|first= Tracey|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1990-11-25}}</ref>

Though Harold ran up significant amounts of personal debt during his ownership of MLGL, he made the company very profitable, so much so that MLG became known as the "Cashbox on Carlton Street", referring to the address of the arena.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=4tlXuNrwjsYC&pg=PT416&lpg=PT416|title=The Lives of Conn Smythe|first=Kelly|last=McParland|year=2011|publisher=[[Random House]]}}</ref>  Upon Harold's death in April 1990,<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/> most of his estate, which was worth less than $50 million, was left to charitable organizations.<ref name=deepdebt/>  The executors of Harold's will were supermarket tycoon [[Steve Stavro]], Giffin and [[Donald Crump]]. In November 1990 Molson exercised their option on 19.9% of the company, paying $10,000 for 735,575 of HEBL's MLGL shares, which at the time were valued at $20 million.<ref name=molsonnets/>  Due to restrictions against cross-ownership in the NHL, the company set up a trust to hold their stake,<ref name=molsonnets>{{cite news|title=Molson nets share of Maple Leafs|date=1990-11-02|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=molsonpurchase>{{cite news|title=Molson to purchase $20 million in Gardens shares for $10,000|newspaper=[[Kitchener-Waterloo Record]]|date=1990-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Molson puts shares of Gardens in trust|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1990-11-01}}</ref> and the league instructed them to sell the shares within an "adequate amount of time".<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay/><ref name=Molsondeal/>  Shortly after the estate, which had limited income due to HEBL still owing TD Bank $15.8 million on its loan to acquire Harold Jr's HEBL stock, missed a January 1991 deadline to repay its $20 million loan (including interest) from Molson,<ref name=missdeadline/><ref name=cantpay>{{cite news|title=TD payments left Ballard with no cash for Molson|date=1991-01-04|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Van Alphen|first=Tony}}</ref> Stavro personally loaned the estate the funds to pay off the debt.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard loses in court to Stavro|newspaper=[[Windsor Star]]|date=1991-04-13}}</ref>  In exchange he received an option to purchase the estate's HEBL shares before January 1996.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=deepdebt>{{cite news|title=Ballard's estate deeper in debt despite Leafs season|date=1993-06-25|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]}}</ref><ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/>  Bill challenged the transaction, but it was approved by the court.<ref name=billjoins/>  In early 1991 Molson offered to buy the estate's shares for $40 each.<ref name=billjoins/>  In September 1991 Bill sold his HEBL stock to his father's estate for $21 million, giving it ownership of the entire company.<ref name=Molsondeal>{{cite news|title=Molson deal gives Stavro total control of Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1991-09-24}}</ref>  Shortly thereafter it was announced that Stavro had reached a deal with Molson on an option to purchase their MLGL shares until April 1994 and for Molson to waive their option on the estate's shares.<ref name=deepdebt/><ref name=Molsondeal/>

===Steve Stavro===
{{chart/start|summary=Ownership structure|style=float:right;}}
