{{chart| | | | | | | | | LT | LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}
{{chart/end}}

Stavro founded MLG Ventures (MLGV) in March 1994 with partners [[Toronto-Dominion Bank]] and [[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]].<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc>{{cite web|url=https://www.osc.gov.on.ca/en/10823.htm|title=In the matter of the Securities Act, R.S.O. 1990, Chapter S.5|publisher=[[Ontario Securities Commission]]|accessdate=2014-03-08}}</ref>  MLG Holdings Ltd. (MLGH), of which Stavro owned 80% and TD Bank controlled the remaining 20%, held a 51% ownership stake in MLGV, with the remaining 49% owned by Teachers'.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=bigwins>{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/103.html|title=Big Wins - At the Bank|date=2007-11-26|accessdate=2014-03-16|publisher=[[Forbes]]|first=Christina|last=Settimi}}</ref>  The following month MLGV announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase the 60.3% of MLGL held by Harold's estate for $34 a share or $75 million total, valuing the company at $125 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff>{{cite news|title=The face-off at Maple Leaf Gardens|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1994-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Date-by-Date Story of Gardens Takeover Fight|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/512622201.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+11%2C+1994&author=&pub=The+Spectator&edition=&startpage=C.15&desc=Date-by-date+story+of+Gardens+takeover+fight|newspaper=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|date=1994-11-11|page=C15}}</ref><ref name=slow>{{cite news|title=Slow speed of probe into sale angers Gardens shareholders|date=1994-08-04|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref><ref name=settotake/>  The estate still owned Stavro $23 million at the time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Stavro's Gardens bid enjoys the rink to itself|date=1994-04-11|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen}}</ref>  Molson also sold its 19.9% of MLGL to MLGV in April 1994 for $25 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/>  [[Larry Tanenbaum]]'s company Kilmer Sports purchased a 25% share of MLGH from Stavro in 1996 for a reported $21 million.<ref name=death/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells>{{cite news|title=Stavro sells off part of Gardens NHL expected to give him fast nod for deal with pal|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1996-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/larrytanenbaum_bio.html|title=Larry Tanenbaum|accessdate=2014-03-08|publisher=[[Toronto Raptors]]}}</ref>

MLGV subsequently purchased all the remaining shares and took MLGL private in 1998, after acquiring more than the 90% of stock necessary to force objecting shareholders out,<ref name=rubber>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private Meeting seen as a 'rubber stamp'|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1996-08-06}}</ref><ref name=slow/><ref name=settotake>{{cite news|title=Stavro set to take Gardens private|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1994-05-03}}</ref> and MLGL and MLGV amalgamated.<ref name=death/><ref name=osc/>  The purchase was the subject of a [[Ontario Securities Commission]] (OSC) review, due to allegations that MLGV had engaged in [[insider trading]] by failing to disclose that broadcast revenue was expected to substantially increase,<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=osc/><ref name=quietexit/><ref name=eyeweekly>{{cite web|url=http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|title=Signs of the times|date=1999-04-01|accessdate=2014-03-16|publisher=[[Eye Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317081458/http://contests.eyeweekly.com/eye/issue/issue_04.01.99/rolling/times.php|archivedate=2014-03-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/1999/03/23/Franchises/STAVRO-FOUND-TO-HAVE-MISLED-SHAREHOLDERS-DURING-94-BID.aspx?hl=NHL&sc=0|title=Stavro found to have misled shareholders during '94 bid|date=1999-03-23|accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref name=irregular/> and a $50 million lawsuit from Bill who claimed that Stavro and others devalued MLGL and withheld information relevant to the value of the company prior to the sale of his stock.<ref name=billjoins>{{cite news|title=Bill Ballard joins Gardens battle Files lawsuit seeking return of his shares|first=Tony|last=Van Alphen|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=1996-02-23}}</ref>  Ontario's Office of the Public Trustee, which was charged with representing the charities named by Harold's will as beneficiaries, argued that Stavro had a conflict of interest as both executor of the will and buyer and had not paid market value because there was no public bidding process for the shares.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=billjoins/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=settotake/><ref name=quietexit/>  Several minority owners, including [[Harry Ornest]], who held 3.5% of the company, and [[Jim Devellano]] also objected to MLGV's attempts to take the company private without an auction.<ref name=repeats/><ref name=faceoff/><ref name=slow/>  Stavro and his partners in MLGV reached a settlement in 1996 to pay an additional $23.5 million plus interest to the charities as well as $2.5 million to the minority shareholders who had sued,<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=death/><ref name=repeats/><ref name=rubber/><ref name=quietexit/> clearing the way for them to become the majority owner of MLGL.  They also settled with the OSC in 1999 for $1.6 million, which included a fine and costs.<ref name=quietexit>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoe.ca/NewsStand/LondonFreePress/Sports/2003/06/26/119735.html|title= A quiet exit for Maple Leafs boss|date=2003-06-26|accessdate=2014-03-16|newspaper=[[The London Free Press]]|first=Lance|last=Hornby}}</ref><ref name=eyeweekly/><ref name=irregular>{{cite web|url=http://investorvoice.ca/PI/006.html|title= An irregular regulator|first=Karen|last=Howlett|date=1999-10-20|accessdate=2014-03-16|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  Teachers' invested $44.3 million and TD $9.75 million in the deal.<ref name=otppgraphic>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/documents/10179/20932/MLSE+Infographic/d8ea6bed-5a05-4879-8b29-9e400488a251|title=Play-by-play|accessdate=2014-03-09|year=2012|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref><ref name=longtime/>

Following the merger, the ownership structure of the now defunct MLGV was retained by MLGL.  MLGH was the majority owner of MLGL, holding 51% of the company.  It in turn was controlled by Stavro (55%), with minority shareholders Tanenbaum (25%) and TD Capital Group (20%).<ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/><ref name=otppgraphic/> The remaining 49% of MLGL was owned by Teachers'.<ref name=rubber/><ref name=stavrosells/><ref name=longtime/><ref name=longtime>{{cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/2011/05/11/td-decision-to-divest-mlse-interest-long-time-coming/|title=How TD became a MVP in the MLSE sale|last=Tedesco|first=Theresa|date=2011-05-11|accessdate=2014-03-08|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref>  This tiered ownership structure gave Stavro effective control of MLGL with only a net 29% stake of the company.<ref name=longtime/>  Teachers' invested a further $50 million in the company in the form of a [[convertible bond]] in 1998 to finance the purchase of the Raptors and ACC and complete construction of the arena.<ref name=isnteverything>{{cite news | last = Vardi | first = Nathan | title = Winning Isn't Everything | url = http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2007/1126/096.html#selection-653.27-653.98 | publisher = Forbes | date = 2007-11-16 | accessdate = 2007-11-16}}</ref><ref name=bigwins/>

===Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan===
In 2003 an agreement was reached to restructure the company with Stavro selling his stake to [[Bell Globemedia]] for a reported $120<U+2013>150-million after debt repayments,<ref name=longtime/> the other partners converting their debts into equity, and each partner getting a direct ownership stake in the newly named MLSE, with MLGH being dissolved.<ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/> This left Teachers' as the controlling majority owners of MLSE with 58.4%, and minority partners Bell Globemedia (15.4%), TD Capital with (13.5%) and Tanenbaum, who took over as non-executive chairman, with 13%.<ref name=thoughages/><ref name=isnteverything/><ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  Each owner of MLSE had a right of first refusal on any shares sold, in proportion to their ownership share.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/>  The same year MLSE was internally valued at over $1 billion by Teachers' in its annual report.  In 2008 the [[Toronto Star]] reported that a valuation commissioned by the company concluded that the company was worth $1.5 billion USD.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2008/01/05/toronto_billionaire_eyes_leafs_empire.html|title=Toronto billionaire eyes Leafs empire|date=2008-01-05|accessdate=2014-01-11|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|last=Westhead|first=Rick}}</ref>  On 5 December 2008 CTVglobemedia (the renamed Bell Globemedia) sold half of its 15.4% stake to Tanenbaum for $100 million, making Tanenbaum the second-largest stakeholder with 20.7%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/>  The transaction valued the company at $1.2 billion.  On 20 August 2009 Teachers' announced that it had agreed to purchase the remaining 7.7% stake in MLSE owned by CTVglobemedia, bumping their stake to 66%.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=longtime/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/business/2009/08/20/teachers_pension_plan_boosting_stake_in_mlse.html|title=Teachers' Pension Plan boosting stake in MLSE|date=2009-08-20|accessdate=2014-04-05|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>

===Bell and Rogers===
In December 2010 it was reported that [[Rogers Communications]], owner of the Toronto Blue Jays, was in negotiations to purchase the Teachers' 66% stake in MLSE, with the asking price set at $1.3 billion,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/sports/hockey/2010/12/01/rogers_in_13b_talks_to_buy_majority_stake_in_leafs_empire.html|title=Rogers in $1.3B talks to buy majority stake in Leafs empire|date=2010-12-01|accessdate=2014-04-05|last1=Cribb|first1=Robert|last2=Van Alphen|first2=Tony|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/rogers-leafs-sale/|title=Report: Rogers bids $1.3 billion for MLSE|date=2010-12-01|accessdate=2014-04-05|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]}}</ref> and in March 2011 Teachers' confirmed that their share in the company was for up for sale.<ref name=snapup/><ref name=notforsale>{{cite web|url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/11/25/mlse-not-for-sale-teachers/|title=MLSE no longer for sale: Teachers' Pension Plan|first=Sean|last=Fitz-Gerald|date=2011-11-25|accessdate=2014-03-09|newspaper=[[National Post]]}}</ref>  Tanenbaum's right of first refusal on the shares gave him control over any sale by Teachers'.<ref name=longtime/><ref name=snapup/>  In May 2011 Teachers' announced that they had reached an agreement to purchase TD Capital's 13.5% ownership share, giving them 79.5% of the company and leaving Tanenbaum as the only minority partner with 20.5%, simplifying a sale of their shares.<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=snapup>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/teachers-snaps-up-tds-maple-leaf-sports-stake/article591372/|title= Teachers snaps up TD's Maple Leaf Sports stake|date=2011-05-10|accessdate=2014-03-09|newspaper=[[Globe and Mail]]|last=Perkins|first=Tara|location=Toronto}}</ref>  In November 2011 Teachers' announced that they were taking the company off the market.<ref name=notforsale/>  However, only a couple of weeks later, on 9 December 2011, Teachers' announced the sale of its entire stake in MLSE to a partnership between [[Bell Canada]] and [[Rogers Communications]], in a deal valued at [[Canadian dollar|$]]1.32 billion,<ref name=otppgraphic/><ref name=sportsempire>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/09/us-mapleleaf-rogers-bce-idUSTRE7B80VN20111209|title=Toronto sports empire sold to Rogers and BCE|first=Euan|last=Rocha|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2014-03-16|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> giving the company an [[equity value]] of $1.66 billion and an [[enterprise value]] of $2 billion.<ref name=value>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/rogers-bce-on-verge-of-deal-for-mlse/article4247367/|title= Rogers, BCE on verge of deal for MLSE|last1=Robertson|first1=Grant|last2=Perkins|first2=Tara|publisher=[[Globe and Mail]]|date=2011-12-08|accessdate=2014-04-06|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlse.com/news/otppmlse_120911.aspx|title=OTPP announces sale of MLSE majority interest|date=2011-09-09|accessdate=2014-01-06|publisher=Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment}}</ref> As part of the deal, Tanenbaum increased his stake in the company to 25%.<ref name=sportsempire/><ref name=tsn-mlsepurchase>{{cite web|url=http://www2.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=382315|title=BCE and Rogers team up to buy 75 percent of MLSE|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]|date=2011-12-10|accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otpp.com/news/article/-/article/21045|title=Teachers' completes $1.32-billion sale of MLSE|date=2012-08-22|accessdate=2013-12-27|publisher=[[Ontario Teachers' Pension Plan]]}}</ref> The deal required the approval of Canada's [[Competition Bureau]], the [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (with regards to MLSE's TV channels), as well as the NHL, the AHL, the NBA, and MLS (with regards to each of MLSE's main sports franchises).

The Competition Bureau announced in May 2012 that it would not challenge the transaction, but that it will "actively review" the situation in light of "serious concerns" expressed by various parties, reserving the right to take action at a later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.competitionbureau.gc.ca/eic/site/cb-bc.nsf/eng/03464.html|title=Competition Bureau Statement on Bell and Rogers' Acquisition of Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|author=[[Competition Bureau]]|date=2012-05-02|accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> The NHL Board of Governors approved the sale at a meeting in Las Vegas on 19 June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.tsn.ca/toronto/story/?id=398779|title=NHL board approves sale of MLSE to BCE-Rogers|date=2012-06-20|accessdate=2014-01-11|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref> The final approval, that of the CRTC, was granted on 16 August, with the commission noting that it only had jurisdiction over the TV channels owned by MLSE (the transfer of ownership of which, it decided, posed no major concerns), and not the broadcast rights associated with MLSE's teams.<ref name="crtc-mlse">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2012/2012-443.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2012-443|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|date=2012-08-16|accessdate=2012-08-25}}</ref> The transaction closed on 22 August 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/bell-rogers-now-official-owners-of-mlse/article4493958/|title=Bell, Rogers now official owners of MLSE|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2012-08-22|accessdate=2012-08-25|location=Toronto}}</ref>

{{chart/start|summary=Ownership structure|style=float:right;}}
{{chart|border=0| | | | |TITLE| | | | |TITLE='''Ownership structure'''}}
{{chart| | | | |MLSE | | | | |MLSE=MLSE<br/>100%}}
{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|-|-|.| }}
{{chart| | | ROGBELL | | | | KILMER | ROGBELL=Rogers/Bell holding company<br/>75%|KILMER=Kilmer Sports<br/>25%}}
{{chart| |,|-|^|-|.| | | |!| }}
{{chart| ROGERS | | BELL | | LT | ROGERS=Rogers Communication<br/>50%|BELL=Bell holding company<br/>50%|LT=Larry Tanenbaum<br/>100%}}
{{chart| | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | }}
{{chart| | | BCE | | BMT | | | BCE=Bell Canada Enterprises<br/>74.67%|BMT=BCE Master Trust Fund<br/>25.33%}}
{{chart/end}}

As part of the sale, two [[numbered companies]] were created to jointly hold stock.  Following the restructuring, the ownership hierarchy of MLSE was:<ref name="crtc-mlse" />
* 8047286 Canada Inc. (Rogers/Bell [[joint venture|joint]] holding company) <U+2013> 75%
** [[Rogers Communications]] &ndash; 50% (net ownership 37.5%)
** 7680147 Canada Inc. (Bell holding company) &ndash; 50%
*** [[Bell Canada|Bell Canada Enterprises]] &ndash; 74.67% (net ownership 28%)
*** BCE Master Trust Fund (investment fund of Bell's pension plan) &ndash; 25.33% (net ownership 9.5%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/892971/bell-acquires-ownership-position-in-maple-leaf-sports-and-entertainment-mlse|title=Bell acquires ownership position in Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment - MLSE|author=[[BCE Inc.]]|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref>
* Kilmer Sports (holding company of [[Larry Tanenbaum]]) &ndash; 25%

This ownership structure ensures that, at the shareholder level, Rogers and Bell vote their overall 75% interest in the company together and thus decisions on the management of the company must be made by consensus of the two. (If Rogers and Bell owned their interests directly, either Rogers or Bell could be overruled by its competitor in combination with Tanenbaum.) As such, Rogers and Bell have agreed that their previously four of six (now six of eight) directors on the MLSE board will always vote together, and thus that any disagreements between the two companies will be settled privately without the involvement of Tanenbaum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/hockey/leafs-beat/mlse-board-expected-to-undergo-major-change-after-sale-is-finalized/article4426208/|title=MLSE board expected to undergo major change after sale is finalized|first=David|last=Shoalts|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|date=2012-07-18|accessdate=2013-03-06|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref name=board />  Bell has indicated that the involvement of Bell's pension fund is, at least in part, intended to ensure Bell can retain its existing 18% interest in the [[Montreal Canadiens]], as NHL rules prevent any shareholder that owns more than 30% of a team from holding an ownership position in any other team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/bell-to-keep-canadiens-stake-1.997652|title=Bell to keep Canadiens stake|author=[[The Canadian Press]]|work=[[CBC.ca]]|date=2011-12-09|accessdate=2011-12-10}}</ref>

